WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.490 align:middle line:90%
[SQUEAKING]

00:00:02.490 --> 00:00:04.482 align:middle line:90%
[RUSTLING]

00:00:04.482 --> 00:00:06.972 align:middle line:90%
[CLICKING]

00:00:06.972 --> 00:00:13.460 align:middle line:90%


00:00:13.460 --> 00:00:19.230 align:middle line:84%
TOBIAS COLDING: So last time,
we looked at power series.

00:00:19.230 --> 00:00:23.210 align:middle line:90%


00:00:23.210 --> 00:00:27.620 align:middle line:90%
So you have a sequence a n--

00:00:27.620 --> 00:00:28.495 align:middle line:90%
is a sequence.

00:00:28.495 --> 00:00:31.100 align:middle line:90%


00:00:31.100 --> 00:00:39.170 align:middle line:84%
And then for each x, you
form the new series--

00:00:39.170 --> 00:00:40.210 align:middle line:90%
you form the series.

00:00:40.210 --> 00:00:46.910 align:middle line:90%


00:00:46.910 --> 00:00:51.600 align:middle line:84%
And the series is with an
a n times x to the power n.

00:00:51.600 --> 00:00:55.230 align:middle line:84%
And then you're summing-- you
decide somewhere to start,

00:00:55.230 --> 00:00:59.280 align:middle line:84%
and then you're summing
to infinity like that.

00:00:59.280 --> 00:01:02.370 align:middle line:84%
So something like this--
that's a power series.

00:01:02.370 --> 00:01:06.630 align:middle line:84%
And we looked at a
particular case where

00:01:06.630 --> 00:01:13.530 align:middle line:84%
the a n's-- so example here is
where a n is equal to 1 over n

00:01:13.530 --> 00:01:15.480 align:middle line:90%
factorial.

00:01:15.480 --> 00:01:20.380 align:middle line:84%
And so we got the
function E of x,

00:01:20.380 --> 00:01:26.970 align:middle line:84%
which is the sum from n equal to
0 to infinity of x to the power

00:01:26.970 --> 00:01:31.500 align:middle line:90%
n divided by n factorial.

00:01:31.500 --> 00:01:40.330 align:middle line:90%
And then we used this to--

00:01:40.330 --> 00:01:46.860 align:middle line:84%
we observed that E is
bigger or equal to 0

00:01:46.860 --> 00:01:51.570 align:middle line:90%
for x bigger or equal to 0.

00:01:51.570 --> 00:02:00.770 align:middle line:84%
And we also observed that
E of 0 is equal to 1.

00:02:00.770 --> 00:02:08.570 align:middle line:84%
And we defined literally to
be e this function E of 1.

00:02:08.570 --> 00:02:16.550 align:middle line:84%
And then we defined another
function E to the q,

00:02:16.550 --> 00:02:23.130 align:middle line:84%
where q here is now
a rational number.

00:02:23.130 --> 00:02:25.590 align:middle line:90%
And it was defined--

00:02:25.590 --> 00:02:30.740 align:middle line:84%
in particular, E of 0 was
defined to be equal to 1.

00:02:30.740 --> 00:02:39.170 align:middle line:84%
E of 1 was just defined
to be [INAUDIBLE].

00:02:39.170 --> 00:02:43.310 align:middle line:84%
Then we also-- we assumed,
which we will prove today,

00:02:43.310 --> 00:02:55.580 align:middle line:84%
that capital E of x plus y is
equal to E of x times E of 1.

00:02:55.580 --> 00:02:56.990 align:middle line:90%
So we assume that.

00:02:56.990 --> 00:03:04.230 align:middle line:90%


00:03:04.230 --> 00:03:05.860 align:middle line:90%
And then we defined--

00:03:05.860 --> 00:03:10.950 align:middle line:84%
so this function based
on the little e--

00:03:10.950 --> 00:03:16.530 align:middle line:84%
in particular, e to some
power m if m is an integer--

00:03:16.530 --> 00:03:20.735 align:middle line:90%
is just e times itself m times.

00:03:20.735 --> 00:03:25.620 align:middle line:90%


00:03:25.620 --> 00:03:38.550 align:middle line:84%
And then we defined e to a power
1/n here to be the positive

00:03:38.550 --> 00:03:55.360 align:middle line:84%
number, as it was defined to be
a positive number so that alpha

00:03:55.360 --> 00:03:59.608 align:middle line:84%
raised to the power
n is equal to e.

00:03:59.608 --> 00:04:02.890 align:middle line:90%


00:04:02.890 --> 00:04:09.820 align:middle line:84%
And we also defined e
to a negative integer.

00:04:09.820 --> 00:04:12.310 align:middle line:84%
And this was just
to be defined to 1

00:04:12.310 --> 00:04:19.810 align:middle line:84%
over-- so we defined e to
minus m to 1 over e to the n.

00:04:19.810 --> 00:04:23.650 align:middle line:90%
So this way, we defined--

00:04:23.650 --> 00:04:29.230 align:middle line:84%
this function here-- the power
series was defined for all x.

00:04:29.230 --> 00:04:33.880 align:middle line:84%
And we defined another
function little e of q

00:04:33.880 --> 00:04:37.030 align:middle line:90%
on all rational numbers q.

00:04:37.030 --> 00:04:40.090 align:middle line:90%
And then we saw--

00:04:40.090 --> 00:04:41.710 align:middle line:90%
we assumed this here.

00:04:41.710 --> 00:04:45.980 align:middle line:84%
We saw that these
two functions--

00:04:45.980 --> 00:04:51.910 align:middle line:90%
so E of x is equal to e.

00:04:51.910 --> 00:04:55.100 align:middle line:84%
This function here is only
defined on rational numbers,

00:04:55.100 --> 00:05:01.550 align:middle line:84%
so they're equal for
rational numbers.

00:05:01.550 --> 00:05:04.090 align:middle line:90%
So we saw that.

00:05:04.090 --> 00:05:08.800 align:middle line:90%
And then in the psets--

00:05:08.800 --> 00:05:12.610 align:middle line:84%
pset 5-- I think it's
for both of them--

00:05:12.610 --> 00:05:13.940 align:middle line:90%
you will show--

00:05:13.940 --> 00:05:16.250 align:middle line:84%
Or maybe it's one
for 4 and one for 5

00:05:16.250 --> 00:05:18.086 align:middle line:90%
to show that E is continuous.

00:05:18.086 --> 00:05:23.950 align:middle line:90%


00:05:23.950 --> 00:05:30.230 align:middle line:84%
And you will also
show that E is the--

00:05:30.230 --> 00:05:32.350 align:middle line:84%
so it would also
show the following--

00:05:32.350 --> 00:05:37.703 align:middle line:90%


00:05:37.703 --> 00:05:40.180 align:middle line:90%
that if you have--

00:05:40.180 --> 00:05:45.816 align:middle line:84%
if f and g are two
continuous function--

00:05:45.816 --> 00:05:54.580 align:middle line:90%


00:05:54.580 --> 00:05:57.220 align:middle line:90%
and so they are defined--

00:05:57.220 --> 00:06:03.340 align:middle line:84%
both of them-- both f and g are
defined on the real numbers.

00:06:03.340 --> 00:06:08.530 align:middle line:84%
And you assume that
if you restrict them

00:06:08.530 --> 00:06:14.020 align:middle line:84%
to the rational numbers, then
the two functions are equal.

00:06:14.020 --> 00:06:17.410 align:middle line:84%
So if they're both
continuous and they

00:06:17.410 --> 00:06:20.440 align:middle line:84%
agree on the rational
numbers, then actually,

00:06:20.440 --> 00:06:22.150 align:middle line:90%
they must agree everywhere--

00:06:22.150 --> 00:06:28.016 align:middle line:90%


00:06:28.016 --> 00:06:39.610 align:middle line:84%
on all of R. So in other
words, this one here--

00:06:39.610 --> 00:06:41.560 align:middle line:90%
this is a function--

00:06:41.560 --> 00:06:46.490 align:middle line:84%
by pset 5, it's a function
that's continuous on all of R.

00:06:46.490 --> 00:06:49.270 align:middle line:90%
It agrees with this function.

00:06:49.270 --> 00:06:54.230 align:middle line:84%
And so this is
the only extension

00:06:54.230 --> 00:06:58.370 align:middle line:84%
of this function to be
continuous and defined

00:06:58.370 --> 00:07:01.430 align:middle line:90%
on all of R.

00:07:01.430 --> 00:07:05.270 align:middle line:84%
So now-- but we still
needed to prove--

00:07:05.270 --> 00:07:08.810 align:middle line:84%
we still needed to prove
this relationship here

00:07:08.810 --> 00:07:10.490 align:middle line:90%
that we assumed.

00:07:10.490 --> 00:07:12.810 align:middle line:84%
So let's try to
prove this one here.

00:07:12.810 --> 00:07:17.270 align:middle line:84%
And I will just do
the main case of it.

00:07:17.270 --> 00:07:19.960 align:middle line:84%
And so we're going to
prove-- so theorem--

00:07:19.960 --> 00:07:22.640 align:middle line:90%


00:07:22.640 --> 00:07:30.080 align:middle line:84%
to prove that E of x times
y is equal to E of x times E

00:07:30.080 --> 00:07:31.670 align:middle line:90%
to the y.

00:07:31.670 --> 00:07:43.670 align:middle line:84%
And I am going to show
this proof in the case

00:07:43.670 --> 00:07:50.610 align:middle line:84%
where these are non-negative
numbers, both of them.

00:07:50.610 --> 00:07:52.420 align:middle line:90%
The general case is--

00:07:52.420 --> 00:07:55.090 align:middle line:84%
once you have this, the general
case is not very difficult,

00:07:55.090 --> 00:07:59.040 align:middle line:90%
but I won't do the general case.

00:07:59.040 --> 00:08:02.200 align:middle line:84%
Now, how are we
going to prove that?

00:08:02.200 --> 00:08:08.320 align:middle line:84%
So to prove that, we're
going to use another theorem.

00:08:08.320 --> 00:08:10.630 align:middle line:90%
So the other theorem is that--

00:08:10.630 --> 00:08:12.125 align:middle line:90%
so we take two--

00:08:12.125 --> 00:08:15.600 align:middle line:90%


00:08:15.600 --> 00:08:19.450 align:middle line:90%
suppose you take two series.

00:08:19.450 --> 00:08:24.720 align:middle line:84%
Each of them are of
non-negative numbers.

00:08:24.720 --> 00:08:28.680 align:middle line:90%
So the setup is--

00:08:28.680 --> 00:08:31.500 align:middle line:84%
so again, this is going
to go into the proof

00:08:31.500 --> 00:08:33.570 align:middle line:90%
of that theorem over there.

00:08:33.570 --> 00:08:39.090 align:middle line:84%
But the setup for this
theorem is more general.

00:08:39.090 --> 00:08:48.355 align:middle line:84%
I take a series a n, and
I take another serious bn.

00:08:48.355 --> 00:08:51.500 align:middle line:90%


00:08:51.500 --> 00:08:58.640 align:middle line:84%
And I'm assuming that
both a n and bn for all n

00:08:58.640 --> 00:09:05.060 align:middle line:90%
are non-negative, so for all n.

00:09:05.060 --> 00:09:08.250 align:middle line:84%
So these are series of
non-negative numbers.

00:09:08.250 --> 00:09:12.260 align:middle line:90%
And then I form another series.

00:09:12.260 --> 00:09:22.670 align:middle line:84%
We will form a third series,
and that third series

00:09:22.670 --> 00:09:27.880 align:middle line:84%
is going to be defined from
the two previous series.

00:09:27.880 --> 00:09:29.820 align:middle line:90%
And the third series--

00:09:29.820 --> 00:09:34.140 align:middle line:90%
let's call it cn like this.

00:09:34.140 --> 00:09:46.590 align:middle line:84%
And now cn here is going to
be the sum of a i b n minus i,

00:09:46.590 --> 00:09:49.860 align:middle line:90%
i equal to 0 through n.

00:09:49.860 --> 00:09:54.600 align:middle line:84%
So this has the
effect that the index

00:09:54.600 --> 00:10:00.180 align:middle line:84%
of this plus the index of
that is always adding up to n.

00:10:00.180 --> 00:10:05.325 align:middle line:84%
So the sum of the two
indices is exactly n.

00:10:05.325 --> 00:10:08.160 align:middle line:90%


00:10:08.160 --> 00:10:19.390 align:middle line:84%
So that's-- so obviously-- so
note that the cn's here are,

00:10:19.390 --> 00:10:20.910 align:middle line:90%
of course, also non-negative.

00:10:20.910 --> 00:10:22.850 align:middle line:84%
They're just sums of
non-negative numbers.

00:10:22.850 --> 00:10:26.032 align:middle line:90%


00:10:26.032 --> 00:10:31.650 align:middle line:84%
So this is a new series
of non-negative numbers.

00:10:31.650 --> 00:10:45.520 align:middle line:84%
And then the theorem is
that if this series here--

00:10:45.520 --> 00:11:01.510 align:middle line:84%
if this one here and this
one here are convergent,

00:11:01.510 --> 00:11:09.710 align:middle line:84%
then this series here
is also convergent.

00:11:09.710 --> 00:11:15.860 align:middle line:90%


00:11:15.860 --> 00:11:20.215 align:middle line:84%
And we also have
that this sum here--

00:11:20.215 --> 00:11:23.699 align:middle line:90%


00:11:23.699 --> 00:11:28.880 align:middle line:84%
that this sum is just the
product of the two sums.

00:11:28.880 --> 00:11:43.242 align:middle line:84%
So it's the product of
the sum here, like that.

00:11:43.242 --> 00:11:46.230 align:middle line:90%


00:11:46.230 --> 00:11:50.290 align:middle line:84%
So again, we have these two
series of non-negative numbers.

00:11:50.290 --> 00:11:53.620 align:middle line:84%
From those two series,
you form a third series.

00:11:53.620 --> 00:11:55.540 align:middle line:90%
And the third series--

00:11:55.540 --> 00:11:58.440 align:middle line:84%
the idea is that the
third series is kind

00:11:58.440 --> 00:12:00.780 align:middle line:90%
of a product of the other two.

00:12:00.780 --> 00:12:05.070 align:middle line:84%
And the cn's in
the third series is

00:12:05.070 --> 00:12:09.195 align:middle line:84%
given where you take
the sum of the products

00:12:09.195 --> 00:12:15.690 align:middle line:84%
of the elements in the other
two, so that the index is at n.

00:12:15.690 --> 00:12:20.890 align:middle line:84%
And then if the two series you
started with are convergent,

00:12:20.890 --> 00:12:26.010 align:middle line:84%
then this product series
is also convergent,

00:12:26.010 --> 00:12:28.950 align:middle line:84%
and the sum of
the product series

00:12:28.950 --> 00:12:34.852 align:middle line:84%
is really the product of the
sum of the other two series.

00:12:34.852 --> 00:12:37.360 align:middle line:84%
Now-- so that's why
we want to prove.

00:12:37.360 --> 00:12:39.750 align:middle line:84%
And then once we
have this we're going

00:12:39.750 --> 00:12:43.840 align:middle line:84%
to use it to prove
this theorem here.

00:12:43.840 --> 00:12:50.000 align:middle line:84%
And so now, to prove it, let
me just first observe that--

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:52.323 align:middle line:84%
so let me observe
over here that--

00:12:52.323 --> 00:12:59.500 align:middle line:90%


00:12:59.500 --> 00:13:02.750 align:middle line:84%
so let me make a
couple of definitions,

00:13:02.750 --> 00:13:05.110 align:middle line:90%
and then making an observation.

00:13:05.110 --> 00:13:13.900 align:middle line:84%
Let me start with making
some definitions that

00:13:13.900 --> 00:13:15.030 align:middle line:90%
is useful in the proof.

00:13:15.030 --> 00:13:20.200 align:middle line:90%


00:13:20.200 --> 00:13:30.520 align:middle line:84%
So I'm going to just find
S n a just like we usually

00:13:30.520 --> 00:13:39.470 align:middle line:84%
do where we're summing here
from i equal to 0 up to n a i.

00:13:39.470 --> 00:13:46.010 align:middle line:84%
The superscript comes
from the a series.

00:13:46.010 --> 00:13:55.940 align:middle line:84%
And then likewise, I define S
n b to be the sum here of the b

00:13:55.940 --> 00:13:56.720 align:middle line:90%
i's.

00:13:56.720 --> 00:14:09.590 align:middle line:84%
And then I'm defining S n c to
be the sum of the ci's up to n,

00:14:09.590 --> 00:14:11.600 align:middle line:90%
like that.

00:14:11.600 --> 00:14:14.270 align:middle line:84%
And so of course,
you have that-- we

00:14:14.270 --> 00:14:22.680 align:middle line:84%
know that a i, b i, and ci
are all non-negative numbers.

00:14:22.680 --> 00:14:25.590 align:middle line:90%
So this means that convergence--

00:14:25.590 --> 00:14:33.130 align:middle line:84%
so convergence of
any of these series--

00:14:33.130 --> 00:14:41.515 align:middle line:90%


00:14:41.515 --> 00:14:43.990 align:middle line:84%
so convergence, say,
of this one is the same

00:14:43.990 --> 00:14:46.910 align:middle line:84%
as saying that these
numbers here are bounded

00:14:46.910 --> 00:14:48.680 align:middle line:90%
That's by monotone convergence.

00:14:48.680 --> 00:14:50.650 align:middle line:84%
So convergence of
any of these series

00:14:50.650 --> 00:15:07.600 align:middle line:84%
is equivalent to that the
corresponding S n a, b, or c

00:15:07.600 --> 00:15:09.645 align:middle line:90%
is bounded.

00:15:09.645 --> 00:15:14.980 align:middle line:90%


00:15:14.980 --> 00:15:17.480 align:middle line:90%
So that's just an observation.

00:15:17.480 --> 00:15:20.680 align:middle line:84%
And again, this is the
monotone convergence theorem.

00:15:20.680 --> 00:15:23.660 align:middle line:90%
This is by monotone convergence.

00:15:23.660 --> 00:15:37.015 align:middle line:90%


00:15:37.015 --> 00:15:40.280 align:middle line:84%
So that's the monotone
convergence theorem.

00:15:40.280 --> 00:15:45.860 align:middle line:84%
The other thing-- see, I
thought of something else

00:15:45.860 --> 00:15:47.635 align:middle line:90%
I wanted to note.

00:15:47.635 --> 00:15:52.370 align:middle line:90%


00:15:52.370 --> 00:15:56.600 align:middle line:90%
So let's try to prove that.

00:15:56.600 --> 00:16:05.810 align:middle line:84%
So to prove it, let me just try
to think about it for a second

00:16:05.810 --> 00:16:06.540 align:middle line:90%
here.

00:16:06.540 --> 00:16:10.130 align:middle line:90%
So if I'm looking at a1--

00:16:10.130 --> 00:16:16.490 align:middle line:90%
say, a2, plus, up to a n.

00:16:16.490 --> 00:16:20.330 align:middle line:84%
Suppose I'm looking
at this here.

00:16:20.330 --> 00:16:27.230 align:middle line:90%
This is like S n a.

00:16:27.230 --> 00:16:30.980 align:middle line:84%
And I have that S
n a, and suppose

00:16:30.980 --> 00:16:33.855 align:middle line:90%
I'm now looking at the S n b.

00:16:33.855 --> 00:16:39.300 align:middle line:90%


00:16:39.300 --> 00:16:42.561 align:middle line:90%
This here is the S n b.

00:16:42.561 --> 00:16:45.510 align:middle line:90%


00:16:45.510 --> 00:16:51.400 align:middle line:84%
Now, if you just multiply
out the product of these two,

00:16:51.400 --> 00:16:52.830 align:middle line:90%
then you would get--

00:16:52.830 --> 00:16:54.940 align:middle line:90%
and I should have started at 0.

00:16:54.940 --> 00:16:56.190 align:middle line:90%
Sorry.

00:16:56.190 --> 00:17:02.700 align:middle line:84%
Let's start at 0 because that's
what we do up there, like that.

00:17:02.700 --> 00:17:11.190 align:middle line:84%
So now I multiply out, and you
see that you're getting a0, b0.

00:17:11.190 --> 00:17:14.670 align:middle line:84%
And you're getting-- then you
can kind of-- if you try to do

00:17:14.670 --> 00:17:15.390 align:middle line:90%
it--

00:17:15.390 --> 00:17:18.579 align:middle line:84%
so let's try to
multiply this out,

00:17:18.579 --> 00:17:21.609 align:middle line:84%
but let's do it
in an ordered way

00:17:21.609 --> 00:17:23.700 align:middle line:84%
And when I'm talking
about "ordered way,"

00:17:23.700 --> 00:17:28.023 align:middle line:84%
I'm not talking about just
multiplying this one on that.

00:17:28.023 --> 00:17:29.440 align:middle line:84%
You could say
that's very ordered,

00:17:29.440 --> 00:17:36.870 align:middle line:84%
but it's not related
to the c series.

00:17:36.870 --> 00:17:41.960 align:middle line:84%
So I want to just group
things so that they remind us

00:17:41.960 --> 00:17:43.440 align:middle line:90%
of the c series.

00:17:43.440 --> 00:17:44.790 align:middle line:90%
But if I do that--

00:17:44.790 --> 00:17:48.710 align:middle line:90%
so we're starting with this--

00:17:48.710 --> 00:17:52.200 align:middle line:90%
is this multiplied by this.

00:17:52.200 --> 00:17:58.572 align:middle line:84%
Then I take this one here,
multiplied by that, so a0 b1.

00:17:58.572 --> 00:18:01.550 align:middle line:90%


00:18:01.550 --> 00:18:06.035 align:middle line:84%
This here is the only
one where the index--

00:18:06.035 --> 00:18:09.180 align:middle line:84%
the subscripts are
non-negative integers.

00:18:09.180 --> 00:18:14.330 align:middle line:84%
This is the only one where the
sum of the two subscripts is 0.

00:18:14.330 --> 00:18:16.250 align:middle line:90%
If I'm looking at where the sum

00:18:16.250 --> 00:18:18.150 align:middle line:90%
Of the two subscripts is 1--

00:18:18.150 --> 00:18:21.180 align:middle line:84%
this is one of them, but
there is another one,

00:18:21.180 --> 00:18:25.080 align:middle line:84%
and that's where I take
this multiplied by that.

00:18:25.080 --> 00:18:30.440 align:middle line:84%
So I group those
together, so a1 b0.

00:18:30.440 --> 00:18:33.820 align:middle line:84%
And now I want to
collect the ones--

00:18:33.820 --> 00:18:38.140 align:middle line:84%
so those are the only two where
the sum of the subscripts is 1.

00:18:38.140 --> 00:18:42.720 align:middle line:84%
Then if I'm looking at,
when I'm multiplying out,

00:18:42.720 --> 00:18:46.410 align:middle line:84%
where the sum of
the subscript is 2,

00:18:46.410 --> 00:18:51.300 align:middle line:84%
well, I could start with this
one, but then I have to pick b2.

00:18:51.300 --> 00:18:55.650 align:middle line:90%
So I take plus a0 b2.

00:18:55.650 --> 00:18:59.190 align:middle line:90%
Then I could take a1 b1.

00:18:59.190 --> 00:19:03.330 align:middle line:84%
That has also sum
of subscripts 2.

00:19:03.330 --> 00:19:05.920 align:middle line:90%
And the last one is--

00:19:05.920 --> 00:19:10.660 align:middle line:84%
If I take a2, but then the b
have to be the 0 subscript.

00:19:10.660 --> 00:19:13.680 align:middle line:90%


00:19:13.680 --> 00:19:17.550 align:middle line:84%
And now I proceed like this,
so I'm grouping it like this.

00:19:17.550 --> 00:19:20.380 align:middle line:90%


00:19:20.380 --> 00:19:24.070 align:middle line:84%
Now, of course, there's going
to be a little bit of an issue.

00:19:24.070 --> 00:19:28.620 align:middle line:84%
So for a while, everything is--
you see that this thing here--

00:19:28.620 --> 00:19:34.060 align:middle line:84%
this here is what we
call c0, this here is c1,

00:19:34.060 --> 00:19:38.050 align:middle line:90%
and this here is c2.

00:19:38.050 --> 00:19:41.770 align:middle line:84%
And then we presumably
also get c3.

00:19:41.770 --> 00:19:50.980 align:middle line:84%
But then there is a point
where we run into trouble if we

00:19:50.980 --> 00:19:54.565 align:middle line:90%
want to really do it like this.

00:19:54.565 --> 00:19:57.020 align:middle line:90%
So what we get is that--

00:19:57.020 --> 00:19:59.740 align:middle line:84%
so when you do this
multiplication, what

00:19:59.740 --> 00:20:01.790 align:middle line:90%
you will see is that--

00:20:01.790 --> 00:20:09.550 align:middle line:84%
so you see like this--
a0 plus a1, a n--

00:20:09.550 --> 00:20:17.230 align:middle line:84%
what you will see--
times b0, b1, up to bn.

00:20:17.230 --> 00:20:19.900 align:middle line:84%
What you will see--
that this pattern here

00:20:19.900 --> 00:20:22.570 align:middle line:84%
is continuing for
a while, and you're

00:20:22.570 --> 00:20:29.960 align:middle line:84%
getting that this is equal
to c0, c1, plus c2, up to cn.

00:20:29.960 --> 00:20:32.930 align:middle line:90%


00:20:32.930 --> 00:20:38.900 align:middle line:84%
In the cn, this is, again,
where the sum of these indices

00:20:38.900 --> 00:20:41.490 align:middle line:84%
could be this one here
multiplied by that.

00:20:41.490 --> 00:20:46.790 align:middle line:84%
The sum of the
subscripts will be n.

00:20:46.790 --> 00:20:50.180 align:middle line:84%
But if you're now looking at
the next one, the one that

00:20:50.180 --> 00:20:53.180 align:middle line:84%
corresponds to c
n plus 1, you're

00:20:53.180 --> 00:20:58.460 align:middle line:84%
not getting all of the c n plus
1 because one of the c n plus 1

00:20:58.460 --> 00:21:03.570 align:middle line:84%
would be like a to
the n plus 1 times b0.

00:21:03.570 --> 00:21:06.610 align:middle line:84%
But you don't have
that one here.

00:21:06.610 --> 00:21:10.280 align:middle line:84%
So what you get is that
you're getting all of these,

00:21:10.280 --> 00:21:12.256 align:middle line:90%
plus something additional.

00:21:12.256 --> 00:21:18.815 align:middle line:90%


00:21:18.815 --> 00:21:22.950 align:middle line:84%
And the additional is-- because
everything is non-negative,

00:21:22.950 --> 00:21:27.710 align:middle line:84%
the additional thing is
a non-negative number.

00:21:27.710 --> 00:21:30.680 align:middle line:84%
So what we have established
here is that we have--

00:21:30.680 --> 00:21:37.850 align:middle line:90%
so this has shown that S n c--

00:21:37.850 --> 00:21:40.040 align:middle line:84%
this here is-- let me
just write it like this--

00:21:40.040 --> 00:21:42.640 align:middle line:90%
this here is S n c.

00:21:42.640 --> 00:21:57.340 align:middle line:84%
So you see that this
thing here was S n a,

00:21:57.340 --> 00:22:00.280 align:middle line:90%
and this here was S n b.

00:22:00.280 --> 00:22:03.070 align:middle line:84%
So what you have is--
so this inequality

00:22:03.070 --> 00:22:08.350 align:middle line:84%
just tells you
that S n a times S

00:22:08.350 --> 00:22:13.630 align:middle line:84%
n b is equal to S
n c plus something

00:22:13.630 --> 00:22:15.140 align:middle line:90%
positive-- non-negative.

00:22:15.140 --> 00:22:20.230 align:middle line:90%


00:22:20.230 --> 00:22:24.100 align:middle line:84%
So in other words,
this number here

00:22:24.100 --> 00:22:27.950 align:middle line:84%
is less than or equal to
the product of these two.

00:22:27.950 --> 00:22:35.390 align:middle line:84%
So this implies that S n c is
less than or equal to this here.

00:22:35.390 --> 00:22:39.920 align:middle line:84%
But now you see you already have
something, because these here

00:22:39.920 --> 00:22:42.630 align:middle line:90%
were increasing--

00:22:42.630 --> 00:22:46.290 align:middle line:84%
they were increasing because
the a n was all non-negative.

00:22:46.290 --> 00:22:49.010 align:middle line:84%
So these here are
increasing, and they

00:22:49.010 --> 00:22:52.340 align:middle line:90%
are less than or equal to--

00:22:52.340 --> 00:22:55.230 align:middle line:84%
the series was supposed
to be convergent,

00:22:55.230 --> 00:22:57.080 align:middle line:90%
so you have that-- sorry.

00:22:57.080 --> 00:23:05.000 align:middle line:84%
So here I'm using that the S
n a is monotone increasing up

00:23:05.000 --> 00:23:06.010 align:middle line:90%
to the limit here.

00:23:06.010 --> 00:23:12.260 align:middle line:90%


00:23:12.260 --> 00:23:17.120 align:middle line:84%
And likewise, the S n b here
were monotone increasing up

00:23:17.120 --> 00:23:17.770 align:middle line:90%
to the limit.

00:23:17.770 --> 00:23:21.920 align:middle line:90%


00:23:21.920 --> 00:23:23.500 align:middle line:90%
So this thing here--

00:23:23.500 --> 00:23:25.810 align:middle line:84%
so this is smaller
than the limit.

00:23:25.810 --> 00:23:28.360 align:middle line:84%
This is smaller than
the limit of that.

00:23:28.360 --> 00:23:36.830 align:middle line:84%
So this thing here is less
than or equal to the product

00:23:36.830 --> 00:23:37.865 align:middle line:90%
of these guys.

00:23:37.865 --> 00:23:47.160 align:middle line:90%


00:23:47.160 --> 00:23:49.920 align:middle line:84%
And so you see--
and that's supposed

00:23:49.920 --> 00:23:51.850 align:middle line:84%
to be just a real
number, this here.

00:23:51.850 --> 00:23:55.710 align:middle line:84%
So you see that these
guys here are now bounded.

00:23:55.710 --> 00:23:57.210 align:middle line:90%
So this means that--

00:23:57.210 --> 00:23:58.500 align:middle line:90%
because they're monotone.

00:23:58.500 --> 00:24:01.750 align:middle line:84%
It means that that series
is also convergent.

00:24:01.750 --> 00:24:05.850 align:middle line:90%


00:24:05.850 --> 00:24:16.680 align:middle line:84%
So what we have concluded
here is that this series here

00:24:16.680 --> 00:24:17.846 align:middle line:90%
is convergent.

00:24:17.846 --> 00:24:21.530 align:middle line:90%


00:24:21.530 --> 00:24:26.960 align:middle line:84%
And we have that this
infinite sum here

00:24:26.960 --> 00:24:32.000 align:middle line:84%
is less than or equal to the
product of the other ones.

00:24:32.000 --> 00:24:34.210 align:middle line:90%
This is what this here gave us.

00:24:34.210 --> 00:24:39.650 align:middle line:90%


00:24:39.650 --> 00:24:41.840 align:middle line:90%
So this is what we have so far.

00:24:41.840 --> 00:24:54.000 align:middle line:84%
Now, we want to get the
reverse inequality holds.

00:24:54.000 --> 00:24:56.120 align:middle line:84%
So we want the
reverse inequality

00:24:56.120 --> 00:24:59.420 align:middle line:84%
of what is over there so that
we can say that those two

00:24:59.420 --> 00:25:02.155 align:middle line:90%
things here are actually equal.

00:25:02.155 --> 00:25:04.550 align:middle line:84%
Now, let's try to
see how do we prove

00:25:04.550 --> 00:25:06.450 align:middle line:90%
the reverse of this inequality.

00:25:06.450 --> 00:25:12.140 align:middle line:84%
The reverse, we are proving
by examining more closely what

00:25:12.140 --> 00:25:13.165 align:middle line:90%
that product was.

00:25:13.165 --> 00:25:19.700 align:middle line:90%


00:25:19.700 --> 00:25:24.390 align:middle line:84%
So you see-- so what is
this additional thing here?

00:25:24.390 --> 00:25:29.900 align:middle line:84%
So again-- so we have-- we're
looking at this thing here.

00:25:29.900 --> 00:25:41.820 align:middle line:90%


00:25:41.820 --> 00:25:44.220 align:middle line:84%
And what we got is
that this here was

00:25:44.220 --> 00:25:51.690 align:middle line:90%
equal to the sum here of cn.

00:25:51.690 --> 00:25:55.182 align:middle line:84%
But then we have some
additional terms.

00:25:55.182 --> 00:25:57.660 align:middle line:90%
And the additional terms is--

00:25:57.660 --> 00:25:59.970 align:middle line:84%
the thing is that
if you start looking

00:25:59.970 --> 00:26:01.810 align:middle line:90%
at the additional terms--

00:26:01.810 --> 00:26:05.220 align:middle line:84%
so what are the
additional terms?

00:26:05.220 --> 00:26:11.170 align:middle line:90%
You're getting a1 bn--

00:26:11.170 --> 00:26:15.780 align:middle line:84%
that's one where the
sum here is n plus 1.

00:26:15.780 --> 00:26:19.540 align:middle line:84%
And then you also get-- so
this is coming from this--

00:26:19.540 --> 00:26:22.030 align:middle line:84%
sorry, that one here
multiplied by this.

00:26:22.030 --> 00:26:30.340 align:middle line:84%
You would also get
a2 b n minus 2.

00:26:30.340 --> 00:26:37.180 align:middle line:84%
You get an a3 b-- sorry,
not n minus 2, n minus 1--

00:26:37.180 --> 00:26:40.620 align:middle line:90%
b3 n minus 2, et cetera.

00:26:40.620 --> 00:26:43.430 align:middle line:90%


00:26:43.430 --> 00:26:51.175 align:middle line:84%
But all of these here--
and then-- so you get that,

00:26:51.175 --> 00:26:52.900 align:middle line:90%
but you don't get--

00:26:52.900 --> 00:26:55.605 align:middle line:84%
again, you don't get the
one that is missing here--

00:26:55.605 --> 00:27:00.160 align:middle line:90%


00:27:00.160 --> 00:27:04.100 align:middle line:90%
is a0 b n plus 1.

00:27:04.100 --> 00:27:06.050 align:middle line:90%
This one is missing.

00:27:06.050 --> 00:27:11.080 align:middle line:84%
And the other one that is
missing is this one here.

00:27:11.080 --> 00:27:14.170 align:middle line:84%
But otherwise, you get
all of the ones that

00:27:14.170 --> 00:27:19.510 align:middle line:84%
was in the c n plus 1, and
you don't get anything more

00:27:19.510 --> 00:27:22.200 align:middle line:90%
And so this pattern continues.

00:27:22.200 --> 00:27:26.610 align:middle line:90%
So the next term would be a2--

00:27:26.610 --> 00:27:28.020 align:middle line:90%
sorry-- yeah.

00:27:28.020 --> 00:27:30.870 align:middle line:84%
And then you would also
get something where

00:27:30.870 --> 00:27:33.250 align:middle line:90%
the sum of the indices was 2.

00:27:33.250 --> 00:27:37.960 align:middle line:90%
That's like a2 bn.

00:27:37.960 --> 00:27:40.510 align:middle line:84%
But here, you would
be missing more.

00:27:40.510 --> 00:27:45.340 align:middle line:84%
You would be missing
a0 b n plus 2.

00:27:45.340 --> 00:27:48.970 align:middle line:90%
You're missing a1 b n plus 1.

00:27:48.970 --> 00:27:51.820 align:middle line:90%
But you don't get anything more.

00:27:51.820 --> 00:27:55.570 align:middle line:84%
And so the thing is, like
when you continue like this,

00:27:55.570 --> 00:28:00.040 align:middle line:84%
the last one you get is when
you're multiplying that by that.

00:28:00.040 --> 00:28:03.480 align:middle line:90%
And that's a n times bn.

00:28:03.480 --> 00:28:08.936 align:middle line:84%
Those here are the sum
of the indices is 2--

00:28:08.936 --> 00:28:10.720 align:middle line:90%
2n, sorry-- it's 2n.

00:28:10.720 --> 00:28:13.270 align:middle line:90%
But you're missing a lot now.

00:28:13.270 --> 00:28:17.006 align:middle line:84%
You only have one
of many, many terms.

00:28:17.006 --> 00:28:19.630 align:middle line:84%
But it is a term
that all appear,

00:28:19.630 --> 00:28:22.100 align:middle line:84%
and this one would
appear in c 2n.

00:28:22.100 --> 00:28:27.370 align:middle line:84%
And so in this way, what you
have is that this here is less

00:28:27.370 --> 00:28:32.980 align:middle line:90%
than S to the power 2n c.

00:28:32.980 --> 00:28:36.980 align:middle line:84%
They are all in there, but
you will be missing terms,

00:28:36.980 --> 00:28:39.730 align:middle line:84%
but all terms are
non-negative So this means

00:28:39.730 --> 00:28:41.740 align:middle line:90%
that you have that inequality.

00:28:41.740 --> 00:28:44.500 align:middle line:90%
So you see that now we have--

00:28:44.500 --> 00:28:50.800 align:middle line:84%
now what we have here
is that we have--

00:28:50.800 --> 00:28:57.730 align:middle line:84%
what we established
before was the inequality

00:28:57.730 --> 00:29:08.080 align:middle line:84%
that S n c was less
than S n a times S n b.

00:29:08.080 --> 00:29:11.360 align:middle line:84%
But what we have now here
is that this thing here,

00:29:11.360 --> 00:29:15.836 align:middle line:84%
this product, is
less than S 2n c.

00:29:15.836 --> 00:29:19.880 align:middle line:90%


00:29:19.880 --> 00:29:25.130 align:middle line:84%
This one here is squeezed
between this one here and that

00:29:25.130 --> 00:29:28.850 align:middle line:84%
one here, but both these
here converge to the same.

00:29:28.850 --> 00:29:33.175 align:middle line:84%
They both converge
to this infinite sum.

00:29:33.175 --> 00:29:36.190 align:middle line:90%


00:29:36.190 --> 00:29:38.310 align:middle line:90%
So these converge to the same.

00:29:38.310 --> 00:29:43.310 align:middle line:84%
This means that the limit of
this here must also be the same.

00:29:43.310 --> 00:29:50.840 align:middle line:84%
And so this shows that this
here is the reverse inequality.

00:29:50.840 --> 00:29:54.840 align:middle line:90%
So proof-- proof over there.

00:29:54.840 --> 00:30:03.608 align:middle line:90%


00:30:03.608 --> 00:30:07.250 align:middle line:84%
So this is that if
you take two series

00:30:07.250 --> 00:30:12.570 align:middle line:84%
and you form the
product, then that also

00:30:12.570 --> 00:30:16.020 align:middle line:84%
converges if the two series
is non-negative numbers.

00:30:16.020 --> 00:30:23.170 align:middle line:84%
So let me just make a corollary
of this, that, of course,

00:30:23.170 --> 00:30:26.760 align:middle line:90%
if you take a series here--

00:30:26.760 --> 00:30:31.000 align:middle line:84%
and so I'll just do
a trivial corollary,

00:30:31.000 --> 00:30:34.710 align:middle line:84%
but you can see how
you can use this.

00:30:34.710 --> 00:30:37.960 align:middle line:84%
And this is used in
proving the general case.

00:30:37.960 --> 00:30:39.370 align:middle line:90%
So we will only--

00:30:39.370 --> 00:30:42.990 align:middle line:90%
yeah, [INAUDIBLE].

00:30:42.990 --> 00:30:45.280 align:middle line:84%
So suppose I take
two series here.

00:30:45.280 --> 00:30:48.390 align:middle line:90%


00:30:48.390 --> 00:30:52.000 align:middle line:84%
So this is a trivial
corollary of it.

00:30:52.000 --> 00:30:56.820 align:middle line:84%
Suppose I take two series here,
and I know that this one here--

00:30:56.820 --> 00:31:00.130 align:middle line:84%
that they are both
absolutely convergent.

00:31:00.130 --> 00:31:08.640 align:middle line:90%


00:31:08.640 --> 00:31:12.410 align:middle line:84%
If they are both
absolutely convergent,

00:31:12.410 --> 00:31:17.570 align:middle line:84%
then if you take
this series here--

00:31:17.570 --> 00:31:20.730 align:middle line:90%
cn-- sorry, ci--

00:31:20.730 --> 00:31:23.990 align:middle line:90%


00:31:23.990 --> 00:31:28.590 align:middle line:84%
well, this one here I claim
is also absolutely convergent.

00:31:28.590 --> 00:31:41.120 align:middle line:90%


00:31:41.120 --> 00:31:45.518 align:middle line:84%
And again, this
trivial corollary

00:31:45.518 --> 00:31:50.720 align:middle line:84%
is the key ingredient in proving
a more general statement that

00:31:50.720 --> 00:31:54.750 align:middle line:84%
would be used, say, to
prove this inequality here

00:31:54.750 --> 00:31:59.580 align:middle line:84%
when x and y are not--
assumed to be non-negative.

00:31:59.580 --> 00:32:00.870 align:middle line:90%
But I won't get into that.

00:32:00.870 --> 00:32:05.035 align:middle line:84%
But I'll just make this
observation, and get this form.

00:32:05.035 --> 00:32:08.360 align:middle line:90%


00:32:08.360 --> 00:32:12.750 align:middle line:84%
So I claim that this thing here
is also absolutely convergent.

00:32:12.750 --> 00:32:16.270 align:middle line:84%
So again, I'm not assuming
now a sign on these,

00:32:16.270 --> 00:32:19.140 align:middle line:84%
but I am assuming that
they're absolutely convergent.

00:32:19.140 --> 00:32:22.020 align:middle line:90%


00:32:22.020 --> 00:32:26.670 align:middle line:84%
And so if they're absolutely
convergent of proof,

00:32:26.670 --> 00:32:31.740 align:middle line:90%
so absolutely convergent--

00:32:31.740 --> 00:32:34.530 align:middle line:90%


00:32:34.530 --> 00:32:40.980 align:middle line:84%
this just means that the
series here, this one here,

00:32:40.980 --> 00:32:47.620 align:middle line:84%
and this one here
are convergent.

00:32:47.620 --> 00:32:51.300 align:middle line:90%


00:32:51.300 --> 00:32:55.020 align:middle line:84%
That's what absolute
convergence means.

00:32:55.020 --> 00:33:01.740 align:middle line:84%
But now if you're looking
at ci, the ci series--

00:33:01.740 --> 00:33:09.100 align:middle line:84%
this here is the sum here,
i equal to 0 to n of a i--

00:33:09.100 --> 00:33:16.000 align:middle line:90%
sorry-- a i b n minus 1.

00:33:16.000 --> 00:33:19.270 align:middle line:90%
[INAUDIBLE]

00:33:19.270 --> 00:33:24.970 align:middle line:84%
But this means that
ci absolute value here

00:33:24.970 --> 00:33:36.070 align:middle line:84%
is less than this thing here,
absolute value, like that.

00:33:36.070 --> 00:33:38.590 align:middle line:84%
You can take the
absolute value sign

00:33:38.590 --> 00:33:40.490 align:middle line:90%
in under the summation sign.

00:33:40.490 --> 00:33:46.420 align:middle line:84%
So this is less than the sum
here from i equal to 0 to n,

00:33:46.420 --> 00:33:52.210 align:middle line:84%
and then a i times b
n minus i, like that.

00:33:52.210 --> 00:33:55.930 align:middle line:90%


00:33:55.930 --> 00:34:04.616 align:middle line:84%
But now you see that this
here is the corresponding c

00:34:04.616 --> 00:34:11.010 align:middle line:90%
so you could now define--

00:34:11.010 --> 00:34:15.030 align:middle line:84%
so you start with
this sequence a i,

00:34:15.030 --> 00:34:22.270 align:middle line:84%
and I now define a
new sequence b i bar.

00:34:22.270 --> 00:34:26.679 align:middle line:84%
And I do it by just taking
the absolute value like that.

00:34:26.679 --> 00:34:29.860 align:middle line:84%
So I know that this new
series is convergent.

00:34:29.860 --> 00:34:40.380 align:middle line:84%
Likewise, I defined b i bar
to be the b i absolute value.

00:34:40.380 --> 00:34:43.500 align:middle line:84%
And I know that
this is convergent.

00:34:43.500 --> 00:34:51.100 align:middle line:84%
And then I defined a
sequence here, ci bar,

00:34:51.100 --> 00:34:54.463 align:middle line:84%
which is just the absolute
value of the ci's.

00:34:54.463 --> 00:34:57.930 align:middle line:90%


00:34:57.930 --> 00:35:00.790 align:middle line:90%
And I know that this one here--

00:35:00.790 --> 00:35:06.430 align:middle line:84%
so I know that this
here is convergent.

00:35:06.430 --> 00:35:09.670 align:middle line:90%
That's by assumption.

00:35:09.670 --> 00:35:13.900 align:middle line:84%
This one here is
convergent by assumption.

00:35:13.900 --> 00:35:19.780 align:middle line:84%
And this inequality here
proves that this here--

00:35:19.780 --> 00:35:23.440 align:middle line:84%
that the c i bar
is also convergent,

00:35:23.440 --> 00:35:26.980 align:middle line:84%
because this one
here is the one where

00:35:26.980 --> 00:35:30.560 align:middle line:84%
you form the products of these
two convergent sequences.

00:35:30.560 --> 00:35:33.140 align:middle line:84%
So this one here
is also convergent.

00:35:33.140 --> 00:35:42.495 align:middle line:84%
So this here is also
convergent by this theorem.

00:35:42.495 --> 00:35:47.290 align:middle line:90%


00:35:47.290 --> 00:35:49.870 align:middle line:84%
Anyway, that was
just an observation

00:35:49.870 --> 00:35:53.630 align:middle line:84%
that we were getting
this statement out of it.

00:35:53.630 --> 00:35:56.300 align:middle line:90%


00:35:56.300 --> 00:35:58.550 align:middle line:90%
Now, this is also related.

00:35:58.550 --> 00:36:02.060 align:middle line:84%
So why do we have
non-negative here,

00:36:02.060 --> 00:36:05.180 align:middle line:84%
or why do we talk about
absolute convergence?

00:36:05.180 --> 00:36:10.740 align:middle line:84%
So this is a simple fact
that if you take a series,

00:36:10.740 --> 00:36:13.600 align:middle line:84%
if you're trying to
sum infinite numbers--

00:36:13.600 --> 00:36:15.350 align:middle line:84%
we now know how to sum
an infinite number.

00:36:15.350 --> 00:36:18.140 align:middle line:90%
But if you're trying to do it--

00:36:18.140 --> 00:36:20.930 align:middle line:84%
if the numbers
that you're summing

00:36:20.930 --> 00:36:23.840 align:middle line:84%
are all non-negative,
then actually,

00:36:23.840 --> 00:36:26.990 align:middle line:90%
the ordering doesn't matter.

00:36:26.990 --> 00:36:29.810 align:middle line:84%
You can check the fifth
element first and then

00:36:29.810 --> 00:36:34.290 align:middle line:84%
the seventh and then the 119
and then come back and take 1.

00:36:34.290 --> 00:36:37.490 align:middle line:84%
It doesn't matter what
order you do it in.

00:36:37.490 --> 00:36:42.560 align:middle line:84%
But if the numbers
are not non-negative

00:36:42.560 --> 00:36:46.070 align:middle line:84%
and the series is not
absolutely convergent, now

00:36:46.070 --> 00:36:49.190 align:middle line:84%
it certainly matters
because you could end up

00:36:49.190 --> 00:36:51.990 align:middle line:84%
taking all the
negative numbers first,

00:36:51.990 --> 00:36:58.680 align:middle line:84%
and then you get really, really
far down towards minus infinity.

00:36:58.680 --> 00:37:02.120 align:middle line:84%
Then you take a few of
the positive elements,

00:37:02.120 --> 00:37:04.100 align:middle line:84%
and then you take
more of the negative.

00:37:04.100 --> 00:37:08.230 align:middle line:84%
And so then you would
actually stay very far down

00:37:08.230 --> 00:37:12.190 align:middle line:84%
toward minus infinity,
and you would never

00:37:12.190 --> 00:37:14.660 align:middle line:90%
be able to come up again.

00:37:14.660 --> 00:37:20.950 align:middle line:84%
So this is a basic fact, that if
you take a series and the series

00:37:20.950 --> 00:37:24.010 align:middle line:84%
are of non-negative
numbers, then actually--

00:37:24.010 --> 00:37:27.940 align:middle line:84%
and it's converging, then you
can rearrange the ordering,

00:37:27.940 --> 00:37:30.220 align:middle line:84%
and it will still
converge, and it will still

00:37:30.220 --> 00:37:32.290 align:middle line:90%
converge to the same number.

00:37:32.290 --> 00:37:35.770 align:middle line:84%
If you're trying to
sum infinite numbers

00:37:35.770 --> 00:37:42.070 align:middle line:84%
and they are not
non-negative and they

00:37:42.070 --> 00:37:47.025 align:middle line:84%
don't converge absolutely,
then the ordering does matter.

00:37:47.025 --> 00:37:51.370 align:middle line:84%
And this is related to why we
are assuming that all of these

00:37:51.370 --> 00:37:54.110 align:middle line:84%
a i, b i's are
non-negative numbers--

00:37:54.110 --> 00:37:55.490 align:middle line:90%
[INAUDIBLE]

00:37:55.490 --> 00:37:57.320 align:middle line:90%
But we won't get into this.

00:37:57.320 --> 00:37:58.280 align:middle line:90%
You can read about it.

00:37:58.280 --> 00:37:59.700 align:middle line:90%
It's a sort of standard fact.

00:37:59.700 --> 00:38:03.410 align:middle line:84%
It's certainly somewhere in
the book, but it's not fun.

00:38:03.410 --> 00:38:04.880 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: How do
we reconcile that

00:38:04.880 --> 00:38:08.720 align:middle line:84%
with our typical properties,
like the addition operator?

00:38:08.720 --> 00:38:13.820 align:middle line:84%
TOBIAS COLDING: Yeah,
so it's related to--

00:38:13.820 --> 00:38:18.020 align:middle line:90%


00:38:18.020 --> 00:38:20.460 align:middle line:84%
again, this is not
part of the syllabus,

00:38:20.460 --> 00:38:24.335 align:middle line:84%
but I think it's a useful thing
to keep in mind because it also

00:38:24.335 --> 00:38:27.440 align:middle line:84%
explains why we're doing
it in a certain way.

00:38:27.440 --> 00:38:34.140 align:middle line:84%
Suppose you take the
alternating harmonic series,

00:38:34.140 --> 00:38:36.230 align:middle line:90%
Remember that this thing here--

00:38:36.230 --> 00:38:39.470 align:middle line:90%
that's the harmonic series.

00:38:39.470 --> 00:38:41.790 align:middle line:90%
This here is divergent.

00:38:41.790 --> 00:38:45.580 align:middle line:90%


00:38:45.580 --> 00:38:46.860 align:middle line:90%
I actually proved--

00:38:46.860 --> 00:38:51.500 align:middle line:84%
I proved, or at least I outlined
in class, why this series here

00:38:51.500 --> 00:38:53.150 align:middle line:90%
is convergent.

00:38:53.150 --> 00:38:57.110 align:middle line:90%
And this is-- and it's just--

00:38:57.110 --> 00:39:00.300 align:middle line:84%
again, the idea
here is that if you

00:39:00.300 --> 00:39:02.700 align:middle line:84%
take-- so you have
something which is called

00:39:02.700 --> 00:39:05.460 align:middle line:90%
the alternating series test.

00:39:05.460 --> 00:39:06.885 align:middle line:90%
So this is a--

00:39:06.885 --> 00:39:08.260 align:middle line:84%
I'm coming back
to your question.

00:39:08.260 --> 00:39:10.952 align:middle line:90%
Just a second.

00:39:10.952 --> 00:39:13.120 align:middle line:84%
And this is closely
related to that.

00:39:13.120 --> 00:39:20.160 align:middle line:84%
So the alternating series test
is that if you take a sequence

00:39:20.160 --> 00:39:29.400 align:middle line:84%
a n of non-negative numbers
and a n converges to 0--

00:39:29.400 --> 00:39:34.440 align:middle line:84%
let's say that a n converges
to 0 in a monotone way.

00:39:34.440 --> 00:39:37.090 align:middle line:90%


00:39:37.090 --> 00:39:40.210 align:middle line:84%
So an example here of
this would, of course,

00:39:40.210 --> 00:39:44.010 align:middle line:90%
be where a n is 1/n.

00:39:44.010 --> 00:39:47.140 align:middle line:90%
That's a monotone sequence.

00:39:47.140 --> 00:39:50.190 align:middle line:84%
So if you take a monotone
sequence like this-- but

00:39:50.190 --> 00:39:54.370 align:middle line:84%
it doesn't need to
go very fast to 0.

00:39:54.370 --> 00:39:57.710 align:middle line:84%
This one does not
converge to 0 very fast.

00:39:57.710 --> 00:40:00.020 align:middle line:84%
But if you have
that and you're now

00:40:00.020 --> 00:40:06.320 align:middle line:84%
looking at the alternating
series based on it,

00:40:06.320 --> 00:40:08.960 align:middle line:90%
this one here is convergent.

00:40:08.960 --> 00:40:10.500 align:middle line:90%
This one here is convergent.

00:40:10.500 --> 00:40:13.850 align:middle line:90%


00:40:13.850 --> 00:40:16.280 align:middle line:90%
And why is it convergent?

00:40:16.280 --> 00:40:20.000 align:middle line:84%
It's convergent because
of the following thing.

00:40:20.000 --> 00:40:23.360 align:middle line:84%
And this is exactly
what I did when

00:40:23.360 --> 00:40:27.560 align:middle line:84%
I tried to explain why
this here is convergent--

00:40:27.560 --> 00:40:31.800 align:middle line:84%
that you're starting somewhere,
let's say starting at 0.

00:40:31.800 --> 00:40:35.420 align:middle line:84%
Then you're looking
at the first element.

00:40:35.420 --> 00:40:37.500 align:middle line:90%
If you're summing here--

00:40:37.500 --> 00:40:41.300 align:middle line:84%
let's say you're summing
from 1 to infinity.

00:40:41.300 --> 00:40:44.610 align:middle line:84%
If you're summing from 1--
then the first element here--

00:40:44.610 --> 00:40:46.110 align:middle line:90%
this is minus 1.

00:40:46.110 --> 00:40:48.630 align:middle line:84%
This is non-negative, so
this is a negative number.

00:40:48.630 --> 00:40:50.030 align:middle line:90%
So you're going down.

00:40:50.030 --> 00:40:51.260 align:middle line:90%
You're starting at 0.

00:40:51.260 --> 00:40:53.720 align:middle line:90%
You're going down

00:40:53.720 --> 00:40:59.440 align:middle line:84%
The next element-- that will be
positive because it's 2 here.

00:40:59.440 --> 00:41:02.920 align:middle line:84%
So it's positive--
it would go up.

00:41:02.920 --> 00:41:06.420 align:middle line:84%
But it's monotone, so
you don't go as much

00:41:06.420 --> 00:41:08.220 align:middle line:90%
up as you're going down.

00:41:08.220 --> 00:41:10.900 align:middle line:84%
So you're first-- first
you're going down,

00:41:10.900 --> 00:41:12.070 align:middle line:90%
then you're going up.

00:41:12.070 --> 00:41:15.240 align:middle line:84%
But you're going less up,e
then you're going less down,

00:41:15.240 --> 00:41:17.880 align:middle line:84%
then you're going
less up, et cetera.

00:41:17.880 --> 00:41:20.585 align:middle line:84%
And that actually is
forcing it to converge.

00:41:20.585 --> 00:41:23.454 align:middle line:90%


00:41:23.454 --> 00:41:26.205 align:middle line:84%
And so now why is this related
to your question about,

00:41:26.205 --> 00:41:28.030 align:middle line:84%
well, how do you
reconcile these?

00:41:28.030 --> 00:41:30.990 align:middle line:84%
So you see, if you're looking
at something like this

00:41:30.990 --> 00:41:34.910 align:middle line:90%
and you now took all of the--

00:41:34.910 --> 00:41:40.890 align:middle line:84%
if you first took many, many of
the positive elements and then

00:41:40.890 --> 00:41:43.920 align:middle line:84%
one or two of the
negative and then many

00:41:43.920 --> 00:41:48.630 align:middle line:84%
of the positive elements again,
then actually, you could--

00:41:48.630 --> 00:41:50.970 align:middle line:84%
for this series,
if you rearrange

00:41:50.970 --> 00:41:52.710 align:middle line:84%
the order of the
things you're summing,

00:41:52.710 --> 00:41:56.390 align:middle line:84%
and then you could
either get it to diverge,

00:41:56.390 --> 00:41:59.260 align:middle line:84%
or you could get it to converge
to pretty much anything you

00:41:59.260 --> 00:41:59.760 align:middle line:90%
want.

00:41:59.760 --> 00:42:02.590 align:middle line:90%


00:42:02.590 --> 00:42:05.980 align:middle line:84%
So this hopefully
explains why when

00:42:05.980 --> 00:42:11.500 align:middle line:84%
the series is not non-negative
numbers, why the ordering really

00:42:11.500 --> 00:42:12.140 align:middle line:90%
matters.

00:42:12.140 --> 00:42:16.780 align:middle line:84%
And again, this is very
closely related to this

00:42:16.780 --> 00:42:18.350 align:middle line:90%
with the product of things.

00:42:18.350 --> 00:42:19.880 align:middle line:90%
Why it's related?

00:42:19.880 --> 00:42:25.090 align:middle line:84%
Because we're getting
this remainder term.

00:42:25.090 --> 00:42:28.570 align:middle line:84%
We've got something that
was like the remainder,

00:42:28.570 --> 00:42:30.910 align:middle line:84%
and it's the remainder
that you want

00:42:30.910 --> 00:42:34.330 align:middle line:84%
to be small in order to say
that things are converging

00:42:34.330 --> 00:42:35.540 align:middle line:90%
to the same thing.

00:42:35.540 --> 00:42:41.110 align:middle line:84%
And you wouldn't have that
necessarily in general

00:42:41.110 --> 00:42:45.010 align:middle line:84%
unless you're assuming that
the terms were non-negative.

00:42:45.010 --> 00:42:49.600 align:middle line:84%
So let's come back to-- that was
just a little bit of [? side, ?]

00:42:49.600 --> 00:42:53.300 align:middle line:84%
but I hope it makes
things a bit more clear.

00:42:53.300 --> 00:42:55.920 align:middle line:84%
Let's come back to
this theorem here.

00:42:55.920 --> 00:42:57.750 align:middle line:90%
How do we prove this?

00:42:57.750 --> 00:43:00.260 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to prove
it from the theorem

00:43:00.260 --> 00:43:04.520 align:middle line:90%
that we did with that if you--

00:43:04.520 --> 00:43:09.860 align:middle line:84%
so we're going to use this
theorem we just proved,

00:43:09.860 --> 00:43:11.070 align:middle line:90%
which is this theorem here.

00:43:11.070 --> 00:43:12.695 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to
use this theorem here

00:43:12.695 --> 00:43:16.730 align:middle line:90%
to prove that theorem up there.

00:43:16.730 --> 00:43:21.333 align:middle line:84%
So now it's just a matter of
identifying the right series.

00:43:21.333 --> 00:43:26.540 align:middle line:90%


00:43:26.540 --> 00:43:35.750 align:middle line:84%
So this is what
we want to prove,

00:43:35.750 --> 00:43:39.510 align:middle line:84%
this is what we want to
show, and this one here--

00:43:39.510 --> 00:43:47.210 align:middle line:84%
this is the infinite sum i
equal to 0 to infinity x plus y

00:43:47.210 --> 00:43:48.740 align:middle line:90%
to the power n--

00:43:48.740 --> 00:43:53.110 align:middle line:90%
sorry, over-- i--

00:43:53.110 --> 00:43:57.280 align:middle line:90%


00:43:57.280 --> 00:44:03.790 align:middle line:84%
let's call it the sum
from n, like that.

00:44:03.790 --> 00:44:06.090 align:middle line:90%
That's what that series is.

00:44:06.090 --> 00:44:08.710 align:middle line:90%


00:44:08.710 --> 00:44:11.140 align:middle line:90%
And this one here--

00:44:11.140 --> 00:44:17.230 align:middle line:84%
that's the sum x n, n
factorial, and this one here

00:44:17.230 --> 00:44:25.450 align:middle line:90%
is sum y n, n factorial.

00:44:25.450 --> 00:44:33.860 align:middle line:90%
Now, so if I want cn--

00:44:33.860 --> 00:44:39.640 align:middle line:84%
so the idea is that if
I'm writing cn as x plus y

00:44:39.640 --> 00:44:43.150 align:middle line:84%
to the power n
over n factorial--

00:44:43.150 --> 00:44:46.390 align:middle line:84%
suppose I write cn
like this, and I

00:44:46.390 --> 00:44:53.150 align:middle line:84%
write a n x n over
n factorial, and I

00:44:53.150 --> 00:44:59.600 align:middle line:90%
write bn y n over n factorial.

00:44:59.600 --> 00:45:03.390 align:middle line:90%
Suppose I define them like this.

00:45:03.390 --> 00:45:06.180 align:middle line:84%
I already know that
this here is convergent

00:45:06.180 --> 00:45:08.310 align:middle line:90%
and that here is convergent.

00:45:08.310 --> 00:45:09.800 align:middle line:84%
By the way, of
course, I also know

00:45:09.800 --> 00:45:12.780 align:middle line:90%
that this here is convergent.

00:45:12.780 --> 00:45:16.970 align:middle line:90%
But I now have that--

00:45:16.970 --> 00:45:19.250 align:middle line:90%
but I don't have--

00:45:19.250 --> 00:45:23.660 align:middle line:84%
I haven't proved--
but I claim now

00:45:23.660 --> 00:45:29.470 align:middle line:84%
that this cn is really
formed in this way.

00:45:29.470 --> 00:45:30.420 align:middle line:90%
So let's see.

00:45:30.420 --> 00:45:38.240 align:middle line:84%
So cn here-- if I define
cn to be this thing here,

00:45:38.240 --> 00:45:40.590 align:middle line:90%
by the binomial formula--

00:45:40.590 --> 00:45:43.220 align:middle line:90%
so x plus y--

00:45:43.220 --> 00:45:46.130 align:middle line:84%
if you take this
here to the power n,

00:45:46.130 --> 00:45:55.980 align:middle line:84%
this thing here is the sum
here of x i times y n minus i.

00:45:55.980 --> 00:45:58.830 align:middle line:90%
And then the coefficient is--

00:45:58.830 --> 00:46:07.770 align:middle line:84%
sorry-- x i times y to the n
minus y, i equal to 0 through n.

00:46:07.770 --> 00:46:11.770 align:middle line:84%
And the coefficient
is n choose i.

00:46:11.770 --> 00:46:13.280 align:middle line:90%
That's the binomial formula.

00:46:13.280 --> 00:46:29.916 align:middle line:90%


00:46:29.916 --> 00:46:35.670 align:middle line:90%
Now, what is n choose i?

00:46:35.670 --> 00:46:40.740 align:middle line:90%
Well, n choose i--

00:46:40.740 --> 00:46:53.550 align:middle line:84%
this is just n times n minus
1 down to n minus i plus 1.

00:46:53.550 --> 00:46:58.790 align:middle line:84%
This gives you n elements, and
then divided by i factorial.

00:46:58.790 --> 00:47:02.900 align:middle line:90%


00:47:02.900 --> 00:47:07.230 align:middle line:84%
But you can write this
thing here as n factorial.

00:47:07.230 --> 00:47:10.770 align:middle line:84%
If you do that, then
you included too many,

00:47:10.770 --> 00:47:17.100 align:middle line:84%
so you have to divide
by n minus i factorial.

00:47:17.100 --> 00:47:20.930 align:middle line:84%
And then, of course, you
still have the i factorial

00:47:20.930 --> 00:47:25.790 align:middle line:84%
in the denominator, so
you can write it like that

00:47:25.790 --> 00:47:29.450 align:middle line:90%
So this means that the cn here--

00:47:29.450 --> 00:47:36.830 align:middle line:84%
our cn is-- so we defined cn
like this-- x to the power

00:47:36.830 --> 00:47:41.261 align:middle line:84%
plus y to the power
n over n factorial.

00:47:41.261 --> 00:47:45.180 align:middle line:90%


00:47:45.180 --> 00:47:48.750 align:middle line:84%
And if we use the
binomial formula,

00:47:48.750 --> 00:47:50.680 align:middle line:90%
then it was equal to that.

00:47:50.680 --> 00:47:57.480 align:middle line:84%
So this here was equal to 1 over
n factorial sum i equal to 0

00:47:57.480 --> 00:48:07.770 align:middle line:84%
to n x i y n minus i, and
then n choose i-- like that.

00:48:07.770 --> 00:48:13.800 align:middle line:84%
Now I write in this
little equation here.

00:48:13.800 --> 00:48:19.800 align:middle line:84%
And so I get that 1 over
n factorial summing from i

00:48:19.800 --> 00:48:28.140 align:middle line:84%
equal to 0 through n, and
then n factorial, n minus i

00:48:28.140 --> 00:48:35.040 align:middle line:84%
factorial times i
factorial, x to the i times

00:48:35.040 --> 00:48:37.920 align:middle line:90%
y to the n minus i.

00:48:37.920 --> 00:48:42.220 align:middle line:84%
And now you see that
the n factorials here

00:48:42.220 --> 00:48:44.410 align:middle line:90%
cancel with the n factorials.

00:48:44.410 --> 00:48:50.770 align:middle line:84%
So you're left with i
equal to 0 through n.

00:48:50.770 --> 00:48:52.970 align:middle line:90%
And now I can group it.

00:48:52.970 --> 00:48:54.080 align:middle line:90%
I can group it.

00:48:54.080 --> 00:49:04.270 align:middle line:84%
I can write it as x i divided
by i factorial times y

00:49:04.270 --> 00:49:09.290 align:middle line:90%
over n minus i factorial.

00:49:09.290 --> 00:49:14.530 align:middle line:84%
And this is to the power
n minus i, like that.

00:49:14.530 --> 00:49:23.130 align:middle line:84%
But now you see that this here
is exactly when we defined

00:49:23.130 --> 00:49:25.970 align:middle line:90%
a n like this and bn like this.

00:49:25.970 --> 00:49:31.030 align:middle line:84%
This here is exactly the
sum from i equal to 0

00:49:31.030 --> 00:49:36.600 align:middle line:90%
through n of a i b n minus i.

00:49:36.600 --> 00:49:39.270 align:middle line:90%


00:49:39.270 --> 00:49:45.870 align:middle line:84%
And so you see that what we
have is that this thing here--

00:49:45.870 --> 00:49:49.560 align:middle line:90%
so E of x plus y--

00:49:49.560 --> 00:49:52.740 align:middle line:84%
with our definition
of the c's, this

00:49:52.740 --> 00:49:56.345 align:middle line:84%
was just defined to be
equal to this limit.

00:49:56.345 --> 00:49:58.890 align:middle line:90%


00:49:58.890 --> 00:50:04.620 align:middle line:84%
But the cn's is also given
by the product of these two

00:50:04.620 --> 00:50:06.180 align:middle line:90%
other series.

00:50:06.180 --> 00:50:12.030 align:middle line:84%
But this means that it must
be the product of the two,

00:50:12.030 --> 00:50:14.670 align:middle line:90%
like that.

00:50:14.670 --> 00:50:21.970 align:middle line:84%
It's the product of the two
sums, infinite sums, like that.

00:50:21.970 --> 00:50:27.520 align:middle line:84%
But this thing here is,
of course, just E x,

00:50:27.520 --> 00:50:31.270 align:middle line:90%
and this is just E y.

00:50:31.270 --> 00:50:32.370 align:middle line:90%
So this proved it.

00:50:32.370 --> 00:50:37.041 align:middle line:90%


00:50:37.041 --> 00:50:41.500 align:middle line:84%
And again, this here was just
assuming that the x and y

00:50:41.500 --> 00:50:42.770 align:middle line:90%
are non-negative.

00:50:42.770 --> 00:50:45.070 align:middle line:84%
But given what I
said-- also, this

00:50:45.070 --> 00:50:48.040 align:middle line:84%
corollary-- it's not
very hard to prove

00:50:48.040 --> 00:50:49.520 align:middle line:90%
the general case from that.

00:50:49.520 --> 00:50:52.490 align:middle line:90%


00:50:52.490 --> 00:50:56.530 align:middle line:90%
So now-- but I won't do that.

00:50:56.530 --> 00:51:05.180 align:middle line:84%
So let's just talk a little bit
more about continuous functions.

00:51:05.180 --> 00:51:08.210 align:middle line:84%
So let me one more time
just remind you about it,

00:51:08.210 --> 00:51:18.105 align:middle line:84%
and then let me give you a
wild example of a function.

00:51:18.105 --> 00:51:22.225 align:middle line:90%


00:51:22.225 --> 00:51:27.100 align:middle line:84%
So first let me remind
you with continuous.

00:51:27.100 --> 00:51:30.250 align:middle line:84%
So continuous [INAUDIBLE] is a
really important concept, also,

00:51:30.250 --> 00:51:32.320 align:middle line:90%
in this class.

00:51:32.320 --> 00:51:37.160 align:middle line:84%
So I have a function, and it
doesn't need to be defined.

00:51:37.160 --> 00:51:43.370 align:middle line:84%
It's defined, say A on
some subset of R into R.

00:51:43.370 --> 00:51:45.810 align:middle line:90%
And then we say that--

00:51:45.810 --> 00:51:50.490 align:middle line:84%
and then we have some
point x0 in the domain.

00:51:50.490 --> 00:52:12.783 align:middle line:84%
And we say that f here
is continuous at x0

00:52:12.783 --> 00:52:13.700 align:middle line:90%
if the following hold.

00:52:13.700 --> 00:52:17.210 align:middle line:90%
That's for all epsilon.

00:52:17.210 --> 00:52:27.020 align:middle line:84%
For all epsilon greater than
0, there exists delta greater

00:52:27.020 --> 00:52:38.320 align:middle line:84%
than 0 such that if x is in
the domain and x minus x0

00:52:38.320 --> 00:52:47.140 align:middle line:84%
is less than delta,
then the images

00:52:47.140 --> 00:52:50.730 align:middle line:90%
deviate at most by epsilon.

00:52:50.730 --> 00:52:54.500 align:middle line:84%
So this is, again, what
it says to be continuous.

00:52:54.500 --> 00:52:57.370 align:middle line:84%
And here, unlike
the previous couple

00:52:57.370 --> 00:53:01.250 align:middle line:84%
of times when I defined it,
here it's really defined.

00:53:01.250 --> 00:53:05.150 align:middle line:84%
You see it makes total
sense on any subset of R.

00:53:05.150 --> 00:53:09.250 align:middle line:84%
It doesn't need to
be an interval, even.

00:53:09.250 --> 00:53:11.150 align:middle line:84%
So it doesn't need
to be all of R,

00:53:11.150 --> 00:53:12.720 align:middle line:84%
but it does need
to be an interval.

00:53:12.720 --> 00:53:17.830 align:middle line:90%


00:53:17.830 --> 00:53:23.720 align:middle line:84%
Now, so this is what it means
for a function to be continuous.

00:53:23.720 --> 00:53:27.045 align:middle line:84%
Let me give you an example of a
sort of somewhat wild function.

00:53:27.045 --> 00:53:30.550 align:middle line:90%


00:53:30.550 --> 00:53:35.730 align:middle line:84%
And so continuous is
a very nice property.

00:53:35.730 --> 00:53:40.340 align:middle line:84%
It's continuous if it's
continuous at all points.

00:53:40.340 --> 00:53:44.690 align:middle line:84%
Usually, continuous is
a nice property to have.

00:53:44.690 --> 00:53:48.090 align:middle line:90%
Often, it's the bare minimum.

00:53:48.090 --> 00:53:49.850 align:middle line:90%
It's often not enough.

00:53:49.850 --> 00:53:52.940 align:middle line:84%
You want something
more than continuous.

00:53:52.940 --> 00:54:01.850 align:middle line:84%
But of course, other times,
you may have much less.

00:54:01.850 --> 00:54:03.093 align:middle line:90%
So here's an example.

00:54:03.093 --> 00:54:07.970 align:middle line:90%


00:54:07.970 --> 00:54:10.620 align:middle line:90%
So this is an example.

00:54:10.620 --> 00:54:14.600 align:middle line:84%
So it's a function
defined on all of R--

00:54:14.600 --> 00:54:27.590 align:middle line:84%
example of a function
defined on all of R

00:54:27.590 --> 00:54:32.236 align:middle line:90%
that is nowhere continuous.

00:54:32.236 --> 00:54:42.540 align:middle line:90%


00:54:42.540 --> 00:54:46.140 align:middle line:84%
By "nowhere continuous," I mean
that there's not a single point

00:54:46.140 --> 00:54:49.375 align:middle line:90%
where it's continuous.

00:54:49.375 --> 00:54:52.920 align:middle line:84%
And so this is the
function f of x.

00:54:52.920 --> 00:54:55.680 align:middle line:90%
And the function is--

00:54:55.680 --> 00:55:05.880 align:middle line:84%
if x here is a rational
point, then f of x is 0.

00:55:05.880 --> 00:55:15.420 align:middle line:84%
And if x here is an irrational
point, then [? I'm ?] setting it

00:55:15.420 --> 00:55:16.730 align:middle line:90%
equal to 1.

00:55:16.730 --> 00:55:19.410 align:middle line:90%


00:55:19.410 --> 00:55:21.420 align:middle line:84%
So it's a pretty
simple function.

00:55:21.420 --> 00:55:26.820 align:middle line:84%
And so I claim that this is
not continuous at any point.

00:55:26.820 --> 00:55:28.865 align:middle line:90%
And so the thing is that--

00:55:28.865 --> 00:55:35.694 align:middle line:90%


00:55:35.694 --> 00:55:38.290 align:middle line:84%
you see, if you take
any points-- let's just

00:55:38.290 --> 00:55:40.230 align:middle line:90%
take a rational point first.

00:55:40.230 --> 00:55:44.530 align:middle line:90%


00:55:44.530 --> 00:55:49.690 align:middle line:84%
So suppose you take a
rational point here.

00:55:49.690 --> 00:55:52.515 align:middle line:90%
This here is-- x0 is rational.

00:55:52.515 --> 00:56:00.280 align:middle line:90%


00:56:00.280 --> 00:56:03.080 align:middle line:90%
Then you have that--

00:56:03.080 --> 00:56:07.430 align:middle line:84%
if you are looking
at square root of 2,

00:56:07.430 --> 00:56:11.240 align:middle line:84%
we know that this
here is not rational.

00:56:11.240 --> 00:56:12.105 align:middle line:90%
We proved that.

00:56:12.105 --> 00:56:17.920 align:middle line:90%


00:56:17.920 --> 00:56:20.690 align:middle line:84%
We showed that this
is not rational.

00:56:20.690 --> 00:56:27.070 align:middle line:84%
And so in fact, if
you take 1 over--

00:56:27.070 --> 00:56:30.340 align:middle line:84%
sorry, square root
of 2 divided by n,

00:56:30.340 --> 00:56:33.850 align:middle line:84%
where n here is
sufficiently large,

00:56:33.850 --> 00:56:37.190 align:middle line:84%
then you can make this
thing here very close to 0.

00:56:37.190 --> 00:56:39.820 align:middle line:90%


00:56:39.820 --> 00:56:42.220 align:middle line:84%
And then you could
add this thing here.

00:56:42.220 --> 00:56:49.530 align:middle line:84%
So you could look at x0, and you
could look at square root of 2

00:56:49.530 --> 00:56:53.880 align:middle line:90%
over n for n really large.

00:56:53.880 --> 00:56:56.980 align:middle line:84%
If n is really large, you
can make this thing here,

00:56:56.980 --> 00:57:01.810 align:middle line:84%
so this is square
root of 2 plus x0.

00:57:01.810 --> 00:57:05.880 align:middle line:84%
So you could make this
really, really close to x0.

00:57:05.880 --> 00:57:09.210 align:middle line:84%
This thing here
would be irrational,

00:57:09.210 --> 00:57:13.350 align:middle line:84%
and so the value of the
function here would be 1.

00:57:13.350 --> 00:57:15.533 align:middle line:84%
Let's make this a
little bit more precise.

00:57:15.533 --> 00:57:19.980 align:middle line:90%


00:57:19.980 --> 00:57:23.430 align:middle line:84%
And so-- let me
maybe say it just

00:57:23.430 --> 00:57:25.030 align:middle line:90%
before I make it more precise.

00:57:25.030 --> 00:57:28.060 align:middle line:84%
So let's just draw
the graph here.

00:57:28.060 --> 00:57:31.960 align:middle line:90%
So we have here x0.

00:57:31.960 --> 00:57:33.800 align:middle line:90%
We have here this--

00:57:33.800 --> 00:57:36.610 align:middle line:84%
this here is this
irrational number,

00:57:36.610 --> 00:57:38.530 align:middle line:84%
which you could
think about, but it

00:57:38.530 --> 00:57:39.920 align:middle line:90%
doesn't need to be this number.

00:57:39.920 --> 00:57:42.470 align:middle line:84%
It could be anything
that is irrational.

00:57:42.470 --> 00:57:44.510 align:middle line:90%
This one here is irrational.

00:57:44.510 --> 00:57:48.940 align:middle line:84%
And by making n super
large, this here super close

00:57:48.940 --> 00:57:54.010 align:middle line:84%
to x0, the value of
the function here is 0.

00:57:54.010 --> 00:57:58.170 align:middle line:84%
The value of the
function here is 1.

00:57:58.170 --> 00:58:01.480 align:middle line:90%


00:58:01.480 --> 00:58:05.050 align:middle line:84%
And so you see that you
have these points as

00:58:05.050 --> 00:58:08.210 align:middle line:84%
close to this point
here as you want,

00:58:08.210 --> 00:58:11.580 align:middle line:84%
but the value of the
function is very different

00:58:11.580 --> 00:58:22.210 align:middle line:84%
So again, just to spell
it out, given an epsilon--

00:58:22.210 --> 00:58:27.940 align:middle line:90%


00:58:27.940 --> 00:58:37.730 align:middle line:84%
so you see that if epsilon
here was smaller than 1,

00:58:37.730 --> 00:58:45.180 align:middle line:84%
then you would have that
f of x minus f of x0--

00:58:45.180 --> 00:58:48.780 align:middle line:90%
this here is a rational point.

00:58:48.780 --> 00:58:51.960 align:middle line:90%
So this here is--

00:58:51.960 --> 00:58:57.140 align:middle line:84%
this is 0, so this
is just f of x.

00:58:57.140 --> 00:59:04.670 align:middle line:84%
And if this here is irrational--
so if x here is irrational,

00:59:04.670 --> 00:59:07.580 align:middle line:90%
then this here is 1.

00:59:07.580 --> 00:59:14.720 align:middle line:84%
So you would have that you can
choose this irrational point.

00:59:14.720 --> 00:59:35.500 align:middle line:84%
So for any delta, we can
choose x, which is irrational,

00:59:35.500 --> 00:59:42.040 align:middle line:84%
and so that x minus x0 is
smaller than delta, but we have

00:59:42.040 --> 00:59:49.100 align:middle line:84%
that f of x here is
actually equal to 1.

00:59:49.100 --> 00:59:50.980 align:middle line:84%
But this difference
here was supposed

00:59:50.980 --> 00:59:53.755 align:middle line:90%
to be smaller than delta.

00:59:53.755 --> 00:59:55.360 align:middle line:90%
That is not the case.

00:59:55.360 --> 00:59:58.100 align:middle line:90%


00:59:58.100 --> 01:00:02.030 align:middle line:84%
If epsilon is smaller than
1, it's definitely not.

01:00:02.030 --> 01:00:02.980 align:middle line:90%
It's 1.

01:00:02.980 --> 01:00:08.590 align:middle line:90%


01:00:08.590 --> 01:00:13.460 align:middle line:84%
And so similarly, if you
take-- so this was proving--

01:00:13.460 --> 01:00:37.340 align:middle line:84%
so this showed-- so this proof
proved that f is discontinuous

01:00:37.340 --> 01:00:40.380 align:middle line:90%
at all rational points.

01:00:40.380 --> 01:00:45.920 align:middle line:90%


01:00:45.920 --> 01:00:48.140 align:middle line:84%
Now let's prove that
it's discontinuous

01:00:48.140 --> 01:00:51.095 align:middle line:90%
at all irrational points.

01:00:51.095 --> 01:01:00.860 align:middle line:84%
So if x [INAUDIBLE]
0 is irrational,

01:01:00.860 --> 01:01:07.610 align:middle line:84%
then we have, of course,
that f of x0 is equal to 1.

01:01:07.610 --> 01:01:11.880 align:middle line:84%
But we also know that
arbitrary close--

01:01:11.880 --> 01:01:26.040 align:middle line:84%
so for any delta
greater than 0, there

01:01:26.040 --> 01:01:39.540 align:middle line:84%
exists a rational point,
a rational number x,

01:01:39.540 --> 01:01:45.750 align:middle line:84%
so that x minus x0 is
smaller than delta.

01:01:45.750 --> 01:01:52.530 align:middle line:84%
But now, again, we have
that f of x minus f of x0--

01:01:52.530 --> 01:01:56.610 align:middle line:84%
this thing here is 1,
this thing here is 0,

01:01:56.610 --> 01:02:00.900 align:middle line:90%
so this difference here is 1.

01:02:00.900 --> 01:02:04.750 align:middle line:84%
And so you couldn't make
it strictly less than 1

01:02:04.750 --> 01:02:07.365 align:middle line:84%
by having this delta
sufficiently small.

01:02:07.365 --> 01:02:09.910 align:middle line:84%
So this proof is
sort of same thing.

01:02:09.910 --> 01:02:16.830 align:middle line:84%
It proves that the function
is also discontinuous

01:02:16.830 --> 01:02:19.295 align:middle line:90%
at all irrational points.

01:02:19.295 --> 01:02:21.800 align:middle line:90%


01:02:21.800 --> 01:02:26.713 align:middle line:84%
Now, let's talk a
little bit more--

01:02:26.713 --> 01:02:29.970 align:middle line:90%


01:02:29.970 --> 01:02:32.060 align:middle line:84%
so let's talk a little
bit more about some

01:02:32.060 --> 01:02:38.450 align:middle line:84%
of the algebraic rules that
we discussed last time.

01:02:38.450 --> 01:02:40.945 align:middle line:84%
And I wanted to single
out two of them.

01:02:40.945 --> 01:02:50.130 align:middle line:90%


01:02:50.130 --> 01:02:52.590 align:middle line:90%
So we had the following.

01:02:52.590 --> 01:03:09.900 align:middle line:84%
If f and g are continuous
functions and c is a constant--

01:03:09.900 --> 01:03:12.740 align:middle line:90%


01:03:12.740 --> 01:03:16.700 align:middle line:84%
then last time, we talked
about the following.

01:03:16.700 --> 01:03:22.290 align:middle line:84%
We talked about that f plus g,
the sum of these two functions,

01:03:22.290 --> 01:03:23.626 align:middle line:90%
is also continuous.

01:03:23.626 --> 01:03:30.450 align:middle line:90%


01:03:30.450 --> 01:03:34.380 align:middle line:84%
We talked about that
if you take a function

01:03:34.380 --> 01:03:36.580 align:middle line:84%
and you multiply
it by a constant,

01:03:36.580 --> 01:03:39.690 align:middle line:90%
this is also continuous.

01:03:39.690 --> 01:03:43.980 align:middle line:84%
We talked about that
if you're looking

01:03:43.980 --> 01:03:47.040 align:middle line:84%
at the product of
these functions, that's

01:03:47.040 --> 01:03:48.870 align:middle line:90%
also continuous.

01:03:48.870 --> 01:03:52.620 align:middle line:84%
The ones we mentioned,
but we didn't actually--

01:03:52.620 --> 01:03:57.600 align:middle line:84%
this here was so elementary,
this one here I outlined,

01:03:57.600 --> 01:04:00.730 align:middle line:84%
and let's talk about
the last two properties.

01:04:00.730 --> 01:04:05.230 align:middle line:84%
One is close to what
we had for sequences.

01:04:05.230 --> 01:04:09.640 align:middle line:84%
And that was that if f
here does not vanish,

01:04:09.640 --> 01:04:18.130 align:middle line:84%
it's nowhere vanishing, then
1/f here is also continuous.

01:04:18.130 --> 01:04:21.340 align:middle line:84%
And the last one, which is
sort of different from anything

01:04:21.340 --> 01:04:29.320 align:middle line:84%
we had for our
sequences, is that if you

01:04:29.320 --> 01:04:33.070 align:middle line:90%
have now a function--

01:04:33.070 --> 01:04:36.040 align:middle line:84%
so you have these two
functions, f and g.

01:04:36.040 --> 01:04:38.710 align:middle line:84%
But now I'm thinking
about f here

01:04:38.710 --> 01:04:46.930 align:middle line:84%
as going from, say,
some subset of R into R,

01:04:46.930 --> 01:04:50.120 align:middle line:84%
but it may not [INAUDIBLE]
into some set B.

01:04:50.120 --> 01:04:54.850 align:middle line:84%
This is a subset of R. This
is another subset of R.

01:04:54.850 --> 01:05:03.380 align:middle line:84%
And then I have g here
goes from this set into R.

01:05:03.380 --> 01:05:06.080 align:middle line:90%
It needs to be--

01:05:06.080 --> 01:05:11.420 align:middle line:84%
so you need this here to be
defined on the images of f.

01:05:11.420 --> 01:05:18.650 align:middle line:84%
If you have that, and these two
functions are continuous, then

01:05:18.650 --> 01:05:21.660 align:middle line:90%
if you form the composition--

01:05:21.660 --> 01:05:24.680 align:middle line:90%
so this is g of f of x--

01:05:24.680 --> 01:05:29.426 align:middle line:84%
this new function h
here is also continuous.

01:05:29.426 --> 01:05:38.690 align:middle line:90%


01:05:38.690 --> 01:05:43.520 align:middle line:90%
And so I want to--

01:05:43.520 --> 01:05:46.580 align:middle line:84%
in the few remaining
minutes, I want

01:05:46.580 --> 01:05:49.140 align:middle line:84%
to talk about these
two properties.

01:05:49.140 --> 01:05:52.490 align:middle line:90%


01:05:52.490 --> 01:05:54.860 align:middle line:84%
And I will start
with the last one,

01:05:54.860 --> 01:05:59.090 align:middle line:84%
because that's somewhat
different from stuff

01:05:59.090 --> 01:06:01.880 align:middle line:90%
we talked about last time--

01:06:01.880 --> 01:06:05.400 align:middle line:90%
I mean for sequences.

01:06:05.400 --> 01:06:11.840 align:middle line:90%


01:06:11.840 --> 01:06:19.990 align:middle line:84%
So let's try to prove that this
composition here is continuous,

01:06:19.990 --> 01:06:21.810 align:middle line:90%
so proof of 5.

01:06:21.810 --> 01:06:30.490 align:middle line:90%


01:06:30.490 --> 01:06:41.290 align:middle line:84%
So given epsilon, well, we
know that the function--

01:06:41.290 --> 01:06:43.310 align:middle line:90%
you sort of to start backwards.

01:06:43.310 --> 01:06:45.560 align:middle line:90%
Given epsilon, you know--

01:06:45.560 --> 01:06:46.060 align:middle line:90%
sorry.

01:06:46.060 --> 01:06:50.020 align:middle line:90%


01:06:50.020 --> 01:06:52.400 align:middle line:84%
Let me just say that
I want to prove it.

01:06:52.400 --> 01:07:01.900 align:middle line:84%
Let's show that h, which
is the composition,

01:07:01.900 --> 01:07:09.040 align:middle line:90%
is continuous at x0.

01:07:09.040 --> 01:07:12.980 align:middle line:90%


01:07:12.980 --> 01:07:15.630 align:middle line:90%
And so I want to prove that.

01:07:15.630 --> 01:07:19.190 align:middle line:84%
And for convenience,
I'm just going

01:07:19.190 --> 01:07:25.060 align:middle line:84%
to call the image of x0 under
f, and we'll call that y.

01:07:25.060 --> 01:07:29.180 align:middle line:90%


01:07:29.180 --> 01:07:43.015 align:middle line:84%
So now, given epsilon
bigger than 0,

01:07:43.015 --> 01:07:53.100 align:middle line:90%
since g is continuous at y0--

01:07:53.100 --> 01:07:57.170 align:middle line:90%
note that this is y0.

01:07:57.170 --> 01:08:09.680 align:middle line:84%
So since g is continuous at
y0, there exists a delta--

01:08:09.680 --> 01:08:12.210 align:middle line:90%
let's call it delta g--

01:08:12.210 --> 01:08:17.250 align:middle line:90%
so that if y minus y0--

01:08:17.250 --> 01:08:20.430 align:middle line:90%
if this is less than delta g--

01:08:20.430 --> 01:08:32.729 align:middle line:84%
then the images-- sorry, under
g not under f, but under g.

01:08:32.729 --> 01:08:41.220 align:middle line:84%
So then the images g
of y minus g of y0--

01:08:41.220 --> 01:08:45.319 align:middle line:84%
the images under g is
smaller than epsilon.

01:08:45.319 --> 01:08:51.782 align:middle line:90%


01:08:51.782 --> 01:08:54.930 align:middle line:84%
So this is just because
g is continuous,

01:08:54.930 --> 01:08:57.663 align:middle line:84%
and I'm using that
it's continuous at y0.

01:08:57.663 --> 01:09:00.330 align:middle line:90%


01:09:00.330 --> 01:09:04.926 align:middle line:84%
Now I need to use
that f is continuous.

01:09:04.926 --> 01:09:10.399 align:middle line:90%


01:09:10.399 --> 01:09:14.810 align:middle line:84%
So now I'm thinking
about this delta g

01:09:14.810 --> 01:09:18.720 align:middle line:90%
as my epsilon [INAUDIBLE] in f.

01:09:18.720 --> 01:09:51.800 align:middle line:84%
So from delta g and
the continuity of f,

01:09:51.800 --> 01:10:06.320 align:middle line:84%
there exists delta of f
such that, if x minus x0

01:10:06.320 --> 01:10:12.390 align:middle line:84%
is less than delta
of f, then the images

01:10:12.390 --> 01:10:17.640 align:middle line:90%
f of x minus f of x0--

01:10:17.640 --> 01:10:20.041 align:middle line:90%
the images is less than delta g.

01:10:20.041 --> 01:10:23.610 align:middle line:90%


01:10:23.610 --> 01:10:27.270 align:middle line:90%
But now you see-- now I have--

01:10:27.270 --> 01:10:30.130 align:middle line:90%
this thing here-- f of x--

01:10:30.130 --> 01:10:33.005 align:middle line:84%
this thing here--
this is f of x.

01:10:33.005 --> 01:10:35.670 align:middle line:90%


01:10:35.670 --> 01:10:42.550 align:middle line:84%
And this thing here,
f of x0, was y0.

01:10:42.550 --> 01:10:44.385 align:middle line:90%
So this is the same as this.

01:10:44.385 --> 01:10:47.310 align:middle line:90%


01:10:47.310 --> 01:10:49.510 align:middle line:90%
But now you see that--

01:10:49.510 --> 01:10:52.900 align:middle line:84%
so I have these two
points that they are--

01:10:52.900 --> 01:10:57.100 align:middle line:84%
and where one of them is y0, and
then I have this other point,

01:10:57.100 --> 01:11:03.600 align:middle line:84%
and their difference
is bounded by delta g.

01:11:03.600 --> 01:11:05.770 align:middle line:90%
So I'm in iteration.

01:11:05.770 --> 01:11:08.710 align:middle line:84%
So this means that the
images of these two--

01:11:08.710 --> 01:11:13.780 align:middle line:84%
so this implies that the images
of this thing here under g

01:11:13.780 --> 01:11:23.950 align:middle line:84%
and this here on g-- so g
of f of x minus g of f--

01:11:23.950 --> 01:11:27.730 align:middle line:90%
sorry, g of y0--

01:11:27.730 --> 01:11:30.625 align:middle line:84%
this thing here is
less than epsilon.

01:11:30.625 --> 01:11:34.930 align:middle line:90%


01:11:34.930 --> 01:11:39.370 align:middle line:84%
This is just because that
was how delta g was chosen.

01:11:39.370 --> 01:11:43.390 align:middle line:84%
And you see that one of
them-- one of these two points

01:11:43.390 --> 01:11:49.090 align:middle line:84%
have to be y0, but that's
exactly what it is over there.

01:11:49.090 --> 01:11:51.010 align:middle line:90%
So I have this--

01:11:51.010 --> 01:11:54.910 align:middle line:90%
but you see, this thing here--

01:11:54.910 --> 01:11:56.610 align:middle line:90%
but this thing here is just--

01:11:56.610 --> 01:12:04.470 align:middle line:90%


01:12:04.470 --> 01:12:09.720 align:middle line:90%
but you see that g of f of x--

01:12:09.720 --> 01:12:11.950 align:middle line:90%
this is just the composition.

01:12:11.950 --> 01:12:16.320 align:middle line:90%
So this is what we call h of x.

01:12:16.320 --> 01:12:27.660 align:middle line:84%
g of y0, where y0 was
defined to be f of x0--

01:12:27.660 --> 01:12:34.680 align:middle line:84%
so this thing here
is g of f of x0.

01:12:34.680 --> 01:12:39.330 align:middle line:84%
But that's just the
composition at x0.

01:12:39.330 --> 01:12:42.550 align:middle line:84%
So you see, what
we have now is--

01:12:42.550 --> 01:12:50.610 align:middle line:84%
So therefore, we have
that if x minus x0--

01:12:50.610 --> 01:12:55.890 align:middle line:84%
if this thing here is
less than this delta f,

01:12:55.890 --> 01:13:00.520 align:middle line:90%
then we have this thing here.

01:13:00.520 --> 01:13:09.580 align:middle line:84%
But this thing here is
h of x minus h of x0

01:13:09.580 --> 01:13:11.860 align:middle line:90%
is less than epsilon.

01:13:11.860 --> 01:13:15.490 align:middle line:84%
And so this proves that the
composition of these two

01:13:15.490 --> 01:13:18.280 align:middle line:90%
functions is continuous.

01:13:18.280 --> 01:13:22.420 align:middle line:84%
And so again, when
you have two functions

01:13:22.420 --> 01:13:24.910 align:middle line:84%
and you look at the
composition, it's

01:13:24.910 --> 01:13:30.770 align:middle line:84%
really important to first check
that the second one is defined.

01:13:30.770 --> 01:13:35.230 align:middle line:84%
So the second one
should be defined where

01:13:35.230 --> 01:13:37.945 align:middle line:90%
you end up under the first map.

01:13:37.945 --> 01:13:50.590 align:middle line:90%


01:13:50.590 --> 01:13:52.720 align:middle line:84%
So now let me just
say a few words

01:13:52.720 --> 01:13:57.700 align:middle line:90%
about the other one, number 4.

01:13:57.700 --> 01:14:10.280 align:middle line:84%
But the number 4 is closer to
things we had for sequences.

01:14:10.280 --> 01:14:12.415 align:middle line:90%
So we have now proven [? 4. ?]

01:14:12.415 --> 01:14:17.780 align:middle line:90%


01:14:17.780 --> 01:14:23.420 align:middle line:84%
So what we have is we have
this function, it's never 0,

01:14:23.420 --> 01:14:29.270 align:middle line:84%
and we have some
x0 in the domain,

01:14:29.270 --> 01:14:32.016 align:middle line:84%
and we know that f
here is continuous.

01:14:32.016 --> 01:14:37.730 align:middle line:90%


01:14:37.730 --> 01:14:40.890 align:middle line:84%
We only need it to
be continuous at x0.

01:14:40.890 --> 01:15:00.580 align:middle line:84%
And then I want to show that
1/f of x is continuous at x0.

01:15:00.580 --> 01:15:03.250 align:middle line:90%
And so I'm looking at--

01:15:03.250 --> 01:15:06.825 align:middle line:84%
so I want to estimate
this difference here.

01:15:06.825 --> 01:15:10.720 align:middle line:90%


01:15:10.720 --> 01:15:15.400 align:middle line:84%
And I want to say that if
I pick an epsilon, then

01:15:15.400 --> 01:15:17.660 align:middle line:90%
I can pick x as close--

01:15:17.660 --> 01:15:22.720 align:middle line:84%
if I pick x to be within delta,
where delta is sufficiently

01:15:22.720 --> 01:15:25.960 align:middle line:84%
small, of x0, then
this difference here

01:15:25.960 --> 01:15:28.450 align:middle line:90%
can be smaller than epsilon.

01:15:28.450 --> 01:15:34.270 align:middle line:84%
So now, let me just
estimate this thing here.

01:15:34.270 --> 01:15:37.610 align:middle line:90%
And so this thing here is just--

01:15:37.610 --> 01:15:40.310 align:middle line:84%
so now I just put it on
the common denominator.

01:15:40.310 --> 01:15:46.030 align:middle line:84%
So I have f of x0
minus f of x divided

01:15:46.030 --> 01:15:56.410 align:middle line:90%
by f of x0 f of x [INAUDIBLE].

01:15:56.410 --> 01:15:59.790 align:middle line:84%
And now it's sort of
the usual problem,

01:15:59.790 --> 01:16:02.090 align:middle line:84%
but now we're maybe
not so worried

01:16:02.090 --> 01:16:04.610 align:middle line:90%
about that usual problem.

01:16:04.610 --> 01:16:08.370 align:middle line:84%
The usual problem
is this x0 is fixed,

01:16:08.370 --> 01:16:10.140 align:middle line:90%
so this is just some number.

01:16:10.140 --> 01:16:12.270 align:middle line:84%
So that doesn't really
matter too much.

01:16:12.270 --> 01:16:17.340 align:middle line:84%
This one here is not fixed,
so that's the usual problem.

01:16:17.340 --> 01:16:19.790 align:middle line:84%
This is a problem
we've seen before.

01:16:19.790 --> 01:16:23.570 align:middle line:84%
We saw it in 3 up there, and
we saw it in the similar things

01:16:23.570 --> 01:16:26.750 align:middle line:90%
for sequences.

01:16:26.750 --> 01:16:45.290 align:middle line:84%
But now the thing is that since
f of x0 is not equal to 0, then

01:16:45.290 --> 01:16:47.100 align:middle line:90%
you can just take--

01:16:47.100 --> 01:16:49.135 align:middle line:90%
so then now you can first take--

01:16:49.135 --> 01:16:52.110 align:middle line:90%


01:16:52.110 --> 01:17:03.570 align:middle line:84%
so now we're going to pick the
delta we want in two steps.

01:17:03.570 --> 01:17:06.700 align:middle line:84%
The first step is since
this here is not 0,

01:17:06.700 --> 01:17:17.430 align:middle line:84%
then we know that there exists
a delta 1 greater than 0 so

01:17:17.430 --> 01:17:23.340 align:middle line:84%
that if x minus x0 is
smaller than delta 1,

01:17:23.340 --> 01:17:29.460 align:middle line:84%
then the image between
f of x and f of x0--

01:17:29.460 --> 01:17:39.150 align:middle line:84%
I can make that smaller
than f of x0 over 2.

01:17:39.150 --> 01:17:45.366 align:middle line:84%
You see, I'm just using this
one here first as my epsilon.

01:17:45.366 --> 01:17:47.430 align:middle line:90%
Once I have that--

01:17:47.430 --> 01:17:52.980 align:middle line:84%
but this here implies,
of course, that f of x--

01:17:52.980 --> 01:17:58.060 align:middle line:84%
see, I have f of x
in the denominator,

01:17:58.060 --> 01:18:01.160 align:middle line:84%
and I want to bound
this here from above.

01:18:01.160 --> 01:18:03.660 align:middle line:90%


01:18:03.660 --> 01:18:04.910 align:middle line:90%
I want to bound it from above.

01:18:04.910 --> 01:18:09.190 align:middle line:84%
So I just need to get a
lower bound for f of x.

01:18:09.190 --> 01:18:12.970 align:middle line:90%
So f of x here--

01:18:12.970 --> 01:18:17.113 align:middle line:90%
so I have that f of x plus--

01:18:17.113 --> 01:18:20.140 align:middle line:90%


01:18:20.140 --> 01:18:23.530 align:middle line:84%
I can write--
sorry, I can write.

01:18:23.530 --> 01:18:35.293 align:middle line:84%
Using this, I can write
f of x0 as f of x minus--

01:18:35.293 --> 01:18:38.680 align:middle line:90%


01:18:38.680 --> 01:18:43.570 align:middle line:90%
sorry, f of x0 like this--

01:18:43.570 --> 01:18:47.775 align:middle line:90%
minus f of x plus f of x.

01:18:47.775 --> 01:18:49.275 align:middle line:84%
Obviously, I can
write it like that.

01:18:49.275 --> 01:18:51.790 align:middle line:90%


01:18:51.790 --> 01:18:58.800 align:middle line:84%
And so this means that f of
x0, slapping an absolute value

01:18:58.800 --> 01:19:03.420 align:middle line:84%
sign on it-- this here
is less than f of x0

01:19:03.420 --> 01:19:07.835 align:middle line:90%
minus f of x plus f of x.

01:19:07.835 --> 01:19:10.590 align:middle line:90%


01:19:10.590 --> 01:19:14.195 align:middle line:84%
And so now I can move this one
here over on the other side.

01:19:14.195 --> 01:19:20.640 align:middle line:90%


01:19:20.640 --> 01:19:23.850 align:middle line:84%
So I have that-- so if
I move this one here

01:19:23.850 --> 01:19:29.820 align:middle line:84%
over on the other side, I get
that f of x absolute value

01:19:29.820 --> 01:19:35.100 align:middle line:84%
is bigger or equal to f
of x0, absolute value,

01:19:35.100 --> 01:19:44.900 align:middle line:84%
minus this difference
here, like that.

01:19:44.900 --> 01:19:50.170 align:middle line:84%
But if I make x and x0
delta 1 close to each other,

01:19:50.170 --> 01:19:53.170 align:middle line:84%
then this difference
here is at--

01:19:53.170 --> 01:19:55.370 align:middle line:84%
it's actually less
than this thing here.

01:19:55.370 --> 01:19:57.560 align:middle line:90%
So there's still another 1/2.

01:19:57.560 --> 01:20:04.960 align:middle line:84%
You see, this one here must be
bigger or equal to 1/2 of f of x

01:20:04.960 --> 01:20:12.160 align:middle line:84%
here, because this here takes up
strictly less than half of this

01:20:12.160 --> 01:20:16.550 align:middle line:84%
thing here, so there's
still another 1/2 left

01:20:16.550 --> 01:20:19.280 align:middle line:84%
And so this gives us a
lower bound for this.

01:20:19.280 --> 01:20:20.540 align:middle line:90%
And now we are out of time.

01:20:20.540 --> 01:20:22.880 align:middle line:84%
but this gives us a
lower bound for this,

01:20:22.880 --> 01:20:28.610 align:middle line:84%
as long as we make sure that
x and x0 is delta 1 close.

01:20:28.610 --> 01:20:30.220 align:middle line:84%
And once you have
that, you can just

01:20:30.220 --> 01:20:32.030 align:middle line:90%
treat this here as a constant.

01:20:32.030 --> 01:20:34.630 align:middle line:84%
And so now it's
clear that you then

01:20:34.630 --> 01:20:39.490 align:middle line:84%
make another choice of
delta, possibly even smaller

01:20:39.490 --> 01:20:41.440 align:middle line:90%
than this one here.

01:20:41.440 --> 01:20:45.130 align:middle line:84%
And then for this smallest
of these two numbers, then

01:20:45.130 --> 01:20:47.710 align:middle line:84%
you can now conclude
that this fraction here

01:20:47.710 --> 01:20:48.970 align:middle line:90%
is smaller than epsilon.

01:20:48.970 --> 01:20:52.580 align:middle line:90%


01:20:52.580 --> 01:20:54.442 align:middle line:90%
Any questions?

01:20:54.442 --> 01:20:55.395 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

01:20:55.395 --> 01:20:57.395 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: I had a question
going back to what we

01:20:57.395 --> 01:20:58.850 align:middle line:90%
were talking about [INAUDIBLE].

01:20:58.850 --> 01:21:01.340 align:middle line:84%
I was a little bit confused
because we're defining

01:21:01.340 --> 01:21:03.270 align:middle line:90%
it to be non-continuous.

01:21:03.270 --> 01:21:07.100 align:middle line:84%
But by definition of
continuity, if you

01:21:07.100 --> 01:21:12.470 align:middle line:84%
picked two x's near each
other that were both rational,

01:21:12.470 --> 01:21:16.310 align:middle line:84%
and their f of x is both 0, then
wouldn't that be continuous?

01:21:16.310 --> 01:21:18.380 align:middle line:84%
TOBIAS COLDING: So
first of all, let

01:21:18.380 --> 01:21:22.397 align:middle line:84%
me say that if you were
to picture this function--

01:21:22.397 --> 01:21:24.480 align:middle line:84%
of course, it wouldn't be
very easy to picture it.

01:21:24.480 --> 01:21:28.760 align:middle line:84%
But you would sort of-- if you
were to draw it, then actually,

01:21:28.760 --> 01:21:29.600 align:middle line:90%
it would look--

01:21:29.600 --> 01:21:31.730 align:middle line:84%
it wouldn't look like
a function anymore,

01:21:31.730 --> 01:21:35.700 align:middle line:84%
because you would have it on
all the rational numbers here,

01:21:35.700 --> 01:21:39.230 align:middle line:84%
it would be 0, and all the
irrational numbers here, it

01:21:39.230 --> 01:21:40.020 align:middle line:90%
would be 1.

01:21:40.020 --> 01:21:42.540 align:middle line:84%
So if you picture it, it
would look like two lines.

01:21:42.540 --> 01:21:45.830 align:middle line:84%
But of course, it wouldn't
be two lines because it's--

01:21:45.830 --> 01:21:47.780 align:middle line:84%
but the points are
just so close together

01:21:47.780 --> 01:21:49.780 align:middle line:84%
that you couldn't
really draw it.

01:21:49.780 --> 01:21:51.680 align:middle line:90%
And so the thing is that--

01:21:51.680 --> 01:21:54.280 align:middle line:90%
but it also means that if you--

01:21:54.280 --> 01:21:56.140 align:middle line:84%
but this picture
here illustrates

01:21:56.140 --> 01:21:59.900 align:middle line:90%
what you're saying, that for--

01:21:59.900 --> 01:22:02.240 align:middle line:84%
if you take rational
numbers, well,

01:22:02.240 --> 01:22:05.140 align:middle line:84%
all the rational
numbers that is really--

01:22:05.140 --> 01:22:07.720 align:middle line:84%
any rational number, whether
it's close or not-- it

01:22:07.720 --> 01:22:09.800 align:middle line:90%
will all be 0 on those.

01:22:09.800 --> 01:22:14.360 align:middle line:84%
So that's not where the
problem with continuity occurs.

01:22:14.360 --> 01:22:17.410 align:middle line:84%
The problem occurs
because you also have

01:22:17.410 --> 01:22:19.430 align:middle line:90%
irrational numbers close to it.

01:22:19.430 --> 01:22:22.990 align:middle line:84%
And it has to be for
all points close to this

01:22:22.990 --> 01:22:25.730 align:middle line:84%
that the value has to
be almost the same.

01:22:25.730 --> 01:22:28.930 align:middle line:84%
So it's really for
the irrational numbers

01:22:28.930 --> 01:22:32.590 align:middle line:84%
that the problem occurs
with continuity--

01:22:32.590 --> 01:22:33.760 align:middle line:90%
in irrational numbers.

01:22:33.760 --> 01:22:36.800 align:middle line:84%
And vice versa for an
irrational number--

01:22:36.800 --> 01:22:39.710 align:middle line:84%
if you're looking at continuity
around an irrational,

01:22:39.710 --> 01:22:42.590 align:middle line:84%
the problem is not from
other irrational numbers,

01:22:42.590 --> 01:22:45.270 align:middle line:84%
but is from the
rational numbers.

01:22:45.270 --> 01:22:48.000 align:middle line:90%